00:04:32.115 --> 00:04:33.740
So what I'm going to
start with is just

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:36.380
a little bit about the
scientific backgrounds.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:38.160
And we're on the
same page on why

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:39.990
we're concerned
about mercury, why

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:44.279
we're having a global treaty
on mercury in the first place.

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:46.070
The reason that mercury
is a global problem

00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:47.486
is the mercury
that we're emitting

00:04:47.486 --> 00:04:49.700
doesn't stay within our borders.

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:54.060
So the main criteria for having
an environmental regulation

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:56.479
internationally-- there's
a general principle

00:04:56.479 --> 00:04:58.520
of international law that
you can do whatever you

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.255
want within your own borders.

00:05:00.255 --> 00:05:01.880
If you're ruining
your own environment,

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.120
it's kind of your problem.

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:07.730
But the minute you start ruining
other people's environments,

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:11.940
that's when it's subject
to international concern.

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:15.990
So if you just emitted
mercury deposited right next

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:19.862
to your power plant or
something and contaminated

00:05:19.862 --> 00:05:21.820
your local environment,
it wouldn't necessarily

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:24.710
be subject to
international regulation.

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:28.107
But mercury in the atmosphere
is in a pretty volatile form.

00:05:28.107 --> 00:05:30.440
And mercury when you're
emitting it's to the atmosphere,

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:32.700
lasts for about half
the year to a year.

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.180
So that means it blows around.

00:05:35.180 --> 00:05:38.100
And it blows around
pretty much globally.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.870
If you think about
watching the weather map

00:05:40.870 --> 00:05:46.750
and about how far weather
goes in different winds,

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:52.450
you get about 7 to 10 days to
go across continents basically.

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:55.812
So in about six months, you
can imagine that something

00:05:55.812 --> 00:05:57.770
that lasts in the atmosphere
that long is going

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:00.150
to mix pretty effectively.

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:02.990
Intra-hemispheric mixing time
is about half the year to a year

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:03.934
as well.

00:06:03.934 --> 00:06:05.850
So anything emitted in
the northern hemisphere

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.840
is going to go to the
southern hemisphere too.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:11.890
So mercury all over the
world in the atmosphere.

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:14.460
Now the reason it's a
problem is because of what

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:16.170
happens when it rains out.

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:19.530
When it rains out, it
accumulates in ecosystems.

00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:21.160
It turns into methyl mercury.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.430
Methyl mercury is even
more toxic than mercury.

00:06:24.430 --> 00:06:28.705
It builds up in food chains--
goes into little fish,

00:06:28.705 --> 00:06:31.100
big fish eat the little fish.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.100
In the Arctic, there's a
really long food chain.

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:37.210
Polar bears eat the big
seals, people eat seals,

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:40.490
you get high levels of
a neurotoxin of concern.

00:06:40.490 --> 00:06:43.100
So methyl mercury
is a neurotoxin.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:50.150
It has effects on people's IQs--
in particular, pregnant women

00:06:50.150 --> 00:06:54.750
who consume things high in
mercury, particularly fish,

00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:56.220
during pregnancy,
their offspring

00:06:56.220 --> 00:07:01.170
have neurological impacts
even at of background doses.

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:03.065
Lower IQ outputs.

00:07:03.065 --> 00:07:07.030
So this comes from a range
of epidemiological studies.

00:07:07.030 --> 00:07:10.240
More recently, lest you
think all of you might be off

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:13.510
the hook, cardiovascular
impacts in the general adult

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:14.740
population.

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:16.970
Some mercury is bad
for everyone, not just

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:20.150
pregnant women and kids.

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:23.030
I'll talk a little bit about
gold mining communities.

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:27.100
Mercury's used in artisanal
and small scale gold mining.

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:31.040
And mercury itself,
at really high levels,

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:35.080
can also be very dangerous if
you breathe in too much of it,

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:38.410
but not really acutely
toxic in the concentrations

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:41.530
that we might likely
be exposed to.

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:44.800
So although it's a concern
to break a thermometer

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:47.010
and you shouldn't
go and sniff it,

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:50.210
you're not going
to expect to see

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:51.940
effects at that
kind of a dosage,

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:55.420
and particularly not at
the dosage of ambient air

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:56.980
concentrations.

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:59.400
But once it gets
into methyl mercury,

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:02.870
once it gets into the food
chain, you have a problem.

00:08:02.870 --> 00:08:07.970
Now think about sort
of what's happened

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:16.440
over the last several
decades in terms of where

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:17.590
mercury is coming from.

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:20.570
So you have mercury
that's used in products.

00:08:20.570 --> 00:08:23.080
Mercury has been
used for millennia.

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:30.140
In cinnabar ore, which is the
really red rock, used as a dye,

00:08:30.140 --> 00:08:32.330
mercury was used in hat making.

00:08:32.330 --> 00:08:35.890
It was used in mining all the
way back to the Roman times.

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:39.110
So it's a very useful substance.

00:08:39.110 --> 00:08:41.590
But one of the really recent
things that's happened

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:44.440
is that mercury is also
a contaminant in coal.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:47.130
So if you look at what's
happened in the Arctic,

00:08:47.130 --> 00:08:49.880
you can look at
the concentration--

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:50.935
this is kind of squished.

00:08:54.790 --> 00:08:58.980
This is sort of
normalized to levels

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:01.400
you can look in various
different archives.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:03.750
So what happens when they
find the unfrozen polar bear,

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:07.280
they can actually look at
what the concentrations are

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:08.980
in the unfrozen
polar bear that died

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:12.320
in the 1200s over here
that was stuck in the ice

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.950
and they found him, as opposed
to current day polar bears,

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:18.220
as opposed to the
museum polar bears

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:20.100
that they killed in the 1800s.

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.210
And you can track that with
things like falcon feathers

00:09:23.210 --> 00:09:25.388
and ringed seal teeth
and various things.

00:09:25.388 --> 00:09:27.846
AUDIENCE: What exactly does
the percent concentration mean?

00:09:27.846 --> 00:09:29.760
Surely, human teeth
are not pure mercury.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:30.610
NOELLE SELIN: Right.

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:34.290
So it's normalized to
present day levels at 100%.

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:36.240
So because the
concentration just

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:37.902
to show everything
on the same scale,

00:09:37.902 --> 00:09:39.735
because the concentration
in polar bear hair

00:09:39.735 --> 00:09:41.490
is obviously different
from feathers,

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:42.780
is different from teeth.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:46.550
So with 100% present
day concentrations,

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:52.866
this is how much it would
have increased relative to.

00:09:52.866 --> 00:09:58.980
So we can do modeling of what
happens in the atmosphere when

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:03.620
you emit mercury and it blows
around all over the place.

00:10:03.620 --> 00:10:06.170
This is what the global
cycle looks like.

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:09.360
It comes from some
of my modelling work.

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:12.581
But again, you're
looking in the Arctic

00:10:12.581 --> 00:10:14.080
where there aren't
a lot of sources.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:15.410
You have a lot of increases.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:18.040
You have health
effects that you can

00:10:18.040 --> 00:10:20.447
estimate hundreds of thousands
of new ones every year.

00:10:20.447 --> 00:10:22.905
So there's growing scientific
concern about this substance.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:27.260
So now what you do about it?

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:29.344
You've got mercury
used in a whole range

00:10:29.344 --> 00:10:30.260
of different products.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:32.710
You've got mercury
coming out of coal.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:36.240
You want to figure out how
it gets into the atmosphere.

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:39.780
So you do something like
an emissions inventory.

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:41.770
And this is what
the UN Environment

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:44.430
Program put together on
anthropogenic emissions

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:46.380
to the air.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:48.080
Coal being about a quarter.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:50.625
This is this artisanal and
small scale gold production.

00:10:50.625 --> 00:10:53.030
I'll talk a little bit
more in detail about that

00:10:53.030 --> 00:10:54.897
and how they get
their mercury later.

00:10:54.897 --> 00:10:56.480
The really interesting
part about this

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:59.530
is we didn't realize that
that was such a big chunk.

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:03.540
I've been working on mercury
for over 10 years now.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:08.110
10 years ago, that wasn't
even in our inventory.

00:11:08.110 --> 00:11:11.176
So realizing how much
mercury was actually

00:11:11.176 --> 00:11:12.550
admitted to the
global atmosphere

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:14.990
from these gold
mining communities

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:18.020
was actually a big step.

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:22.230
And you've got a bunch of
other different all kinds

00:11:22.230 --> 00:11:25.470
of uses of mercury, uses in
the chloralkali industry.

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:27.950
Disposal of waste for
mercury containing products

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:30.130
is a chunk of
emissions to the air.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:36.270
Also important in emissions
to water, releases to water.

00:11:36.270 --> 00:11:39.561
Cremation is always
an interesting one.

00:11:39.561 --> 00:11:41.160
You got mercury in your teeth.

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:42.330
Guess where that goes?

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:43.249
Yeah?

00:11:43.249 --> 00:11:44.790
AUDIENCE: Being a
heavy metal, what's

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:50.960
the mechanism by which say
someone mining for gold-- I

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.505
assuming it has to be
highly atomized to be

00:11:53.505 --> 00:11:55.942
able to go into the
atmosphere and travel a ways.

00:11:55.942 --> 00:11:57.900
NOELLE SELIN: So mercury's
a funky heavy metal.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:01.920
It's the only one that's
liquid at room temperature,

00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:05.440
so you've got elemental mercury
that you can-- basically

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:08.210
thermometer kind of
elemental mercury.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:13.250
And if you put that in a pan
with gold, it'll form amalgam.

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:15.940
And then all you have to
do, you take that amalgam,

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:18.979
you burn, and mercury
will burn off.

00:12:18.979 --> 00:12:19.895
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:19.895 --> 00:12:20.880
NOELLE SELIN: Yeah.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:23.310
So sometimes that's
done in gold shops.

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:26.316
And I'll have a slide
later about the process

00:12:26.316 --> 00:12:27.440
and where the mercury goes.

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:29.690
But that's essentially
the principal.

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:30.940
And that's why it goes to air.

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:34.140
Of course, there's going
to be some rinsing.

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:37.760
And that's why that numbers are
all uncertain, because again,

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:43.260
this is a sector that's
not very regulated

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:44.900
where the mercury ends up.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:47.550
AUDIENCE: Why was it overlooked?

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:50.902
