show up in the rater again?

00:12:50.902 --> 00:12:55.180
NOELLE SELIN: So
it was whether it

00:12:55.180 --> 00:12:58.240
goes to air was the
question, and what fraction,

00:12:58.240 --> 00:12:59.800
and how much is used.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.550
So there weren't
very good estimates

00:13:01.550 --> 00:13:03.780
because this is generally
kind of an illegal sector

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:08.660
in a lot of places, or at least
an unregulated informal one.

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:11.882
So it may actually have
increased over time

00:13:11.882 --> 00:13:13.090
because of the price of gold.

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:18.710
There's more money
to be made in mining

00:13:18.710 --> 00:13:22.710
gold, so more use of mercury.

00:13:22.710 --> 00:13:26.610
And then what fraction you
assume of how much people

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:30.503
actually keep versus
how much they burn off

00:13:30.503 --> 00:13:33.390
has changed over time.

00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:35.570
And just the
difficulty in-- it's

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:39.020
pretty easy to get
coal statistics.

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.760
Actually, I was one
of the first ones

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:45.760
to actually put an estimate
into a global model of artisanal

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:47.330
and small scale gold mining.

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:49.700
And what I did is I just
took the total amount that

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:52.919
was used, which we had
estimates of, and I said,

00:13:52.919 --> 00:13:54.710
these are the countries
in which it's used.

00:13:54.710 --> 00:13:56.840
We're going to assume
30% goes to the air

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:58.080
and I'm just going
to grid it, because I

00:13:58.080 --> 00:13:59.060
didn't know what to do with it.

00:13:59.060 --> 00:14:00.920
Now we have a little
better of a handle on it.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:01.420
Yeah?

00:14:01.420 --> 00:14:07.266
AUDIENCE: What is [INAUDIBLE]
major discovery that

00:14:07.266 --> 00:14:11.090
will change [INAUDIBLE] that
you have showing on the site?

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:13.410
NOELLE SELIN: Probably.

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:18.010
I think that artisanal and
small scale gold mining

00:14:18.010 --> 00:14:20.390
we could learn a lot more about.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:21.870
And the uncertainties are huge.

00:14:21.870 --> 00:14:23.810
So we're doing some
work with the modeling

00:14:23.810 --> 00:14:27.640
and also looking at
measurements in the atmosphere

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:30.430
to try to back calculate
what the emissions are.

00:14:30.430 --> 00:14:32.560
One of the key
uncertainties in emissions

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:36.730
is-- the key is that when you
emit mercury, it doesn't stay,

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:41.300
because it's a volatile
heavy metal, weirdly enough.

00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:44.195
So when it goes into the
soil, something like lead

00:14:44.195 --> 00:14:45.455
will stay there.

00:14:45.455 --> 00:14:47.490
But mercury pops back up.

00:14:47.490 --> 00:14:49.130
And because we've
been emitting mercury

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:51.920
for decades,
centuries, millennia,

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:54.450
there's mercury enhanced in
the surface ocean, enhanced

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:56.100
in the soil, it keeps
popping back up.

00:14:56.100 --> 00:14:59.330
We don't have a good handle
on what that source is

00:14:59.330 --> 00:15:02.870
and how much of it is
human versus natural.

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:07.170
So this actually I
did the human in red,

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:11.672
and then it's technically
pre-industrial.

00:15:11.672 --> 00:15:13.880
But the problem is-- so
there was a recent paper that

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:18.330
came out that said, yes, mercury
circulating in the system

00:15:18.330 --> 00:15:21.610
has gone about a factor of
three since pre-industrial

00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:24.460
and we can use lake sediment
cores to figure that out.

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:27.440
But again, the
Romans used mercury.

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:31.280
So labeling pre-industrial
equals natural

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:33.850
is kind of problematic,
because although we've

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:36.800
had a real big spike
from coal, there's

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:39.310
probably human mercury
that's been circulating

00:15:39.310 --> 00:15:40.784
that we don't have a good idea.

00:15:40.784 --> 00:15:42.700
So they're saying maybe
it's a factor of seven

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:45.370
now as opposed to
a factor of three.

00:15:45.370 --> 00:15:49.550
But regardless, current
emissions play a role,

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:56.500
and if you look at
deposition to the US,

00:15:56.500 --> 00:15:58.950
this is mercury
actually coming down

00:15:58.950 --> 00:16:01.420
in rainfall entering
the US environment.

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:04.770
What you see is you see
a bunch of patterns.

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:08.120
So the highest wet deposition in
the US is actually in Florida.

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:11.190
And that comes from
global sources.

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:13.140
But you can see
that there's also

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:15.330
deposition in the northeast
that comes directly

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:16.500
from the coal power plants.

00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:18.610
So not going to go through
all the chemistry of this

00:16:18.610 --> 00:16:20.026
because it has to
do with chemical

00:16:20.026 --> 00:16:22.010
reactions in the atmosphere.

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:26.220
But the upshot is that if
you want to reduce deposition

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:29.180
over the US in all
these different places,

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:32.260
you have to tackle both the
local sources-- because some

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:36.190
of it actually deposits right
near the source, and some of it

00:16:36.190 --> 00:16:40.490
circulates globally-- and the
global atmosphere deposits.

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:45.900
And then actually affects you.

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:48.330
So this is really one of the
motivating things for the US

00:16:48.330 --> 00:16:51.400
to get involved both
in mercury policy

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:54.540
nationally and mercury
policy globally.

00:16:54.540 --> 00:16:58.730
So just giving you a
little bit of the history.

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:01.520
I'll talk a little bit about
what happened in the US

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:02.890
as well.

00:17:02.890 --> 00:17:07.160
But this is something that's
come up in the last 15 years

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:08.510
or so.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:10.890
The first global
scientific assessment

00:17:10.890 --> 00:17:15.619
of mercury that gave this idea
that mercury is a long range

00:17:15.619 --> 00:17:19.599
problem-- global action
is necessary to address it

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:24.040
was the main conclusion
that came out in 2002.

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:25.890
So you get this
group of scientists

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:29.410
together under the UN
Environment Program Chemicals

00:17:29.410 --> 00:17:33.290
Division and they say, mercury's
a problem, global action needed

00:17:33.290 --> 00:17:34.300
to address it.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:37.360
Now, look, what do we do?

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:42.130
And so the global treaty
as I said was last year.

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:44.850
Now that's a long, long state.

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:48.130
That's 11 years difference.

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:51.600
So what happened
during that time.

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:55.300
Well, what happened was
a lot to do with the US.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:56.940
And this shows sort
of the influence

00:17:56.940 --> 00:18:01.980
of domestic regulation in
the international context.

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:04.590
Those of you who remember
2002 in the US, thee US

00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:09.160
administration wasn't so
pro-internal environmental

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:10.690
regulation.

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:12.950
Didn't really like
the idea of signing up

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:16.790
the US to something that
might be questionable in terms

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:19.470
of its cost benefit ratio.

00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:24.150
And you know, why mercury?

00:18:24.150 --> 00:18:27.640
International cooperation
wasn't necessarily a priority.

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:32.480
International environmental
cooperation even less so.

00:18:32.480 --> 00:18:36.050
And the idea that we shouldn't
waste time getting everyone

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:37.570
on board, we should
just do what we

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:40.090
want to do with the
willing partners

00:18:40.090 --> 00:18:43.274
was an idea that was
sort of widespread

00:18:43.274 --> 00:18:44.190
in the administration.

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:46.550
So they applied that
to mercury as well.

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:49.030
So what they have is the
global mercury partnership.

00:18:49.030 --> 00:18:54.310
They said, let's get
together various coalitions

00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:56.080
that are going to
attack different aspects

00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:57.320
of the mercury problem.

00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:59.800
So they had a task force on
artisanal and small scale gold

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:00.300
mining.

00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:02.590
They had a task force on
coal fire power plants.

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:05.160
And they did some
voluntary activities,

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:06.930
capacity building in
different countries

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:08.380
to try to reduce emissions.

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:12.190
But there was an
ongoing discussion about

00:19:12.190 --> 00:19:14.640
whether that's actually
effective at reducing

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:16.443
the mercury problem or not.

00:19:16.443 --> 00:19:18.890
It's pretty much
keeping the mercury

00:19:18.890 --> 00:19:21.560
levels constant at this point.

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:23.640
And the European
Union in particular

00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:28.270
was very in favor of a
global legally binding treaty

00:19:28.270 --> 00:19:32.570
and had been since 2002.

00:19:32.570 --> 00:19:39.427
So every two years the UN
Environment Program governing

00:19:39.427 --> 00:19:40.010
council meets.

00:19:40.010 --> 00:19:42.790
The governing council is
the environment ministers

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:44.260
of all the nations.

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:48.100
And they're the ones really that
would set a mandate actually

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:49.336
negotiate a global treaty.

00:19:49.336 --> 00:19:51.710
It would be done under the
auspices of the UN Environment

00:19:51.710 --> 00:19:52.470
Program.

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:53.690
Every two years they met.

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:59.740
And in 2000, 2003, US said
now let's do a program.

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:04.970
2005, not so much, US.

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:07.570
Now let's strengthen
the program.

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.810
2007, still nothing, although
a couple of other countries

00:20:11.810 --> 00:20:13.079
are on board by that time.

00:20:13.079 --> 00:20:15.620
Latin America's actually really
interested in doing something

00:20:15.620 --> 00:20:17.661
particularly because of
the concerns on artisanal

00:20:17.661 --> 00:20:20.190
and small scale gold mining.

00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:25.190
Canada also has its phases
of liking or not liking

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:27.560
international regulation.

00:20:27.560 --> 00:20:31.170
In the organic pollutants
example, the last convention,

00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:34.936
Canada was very much in favor
of negotiating something.

00:20:34.936 --> 00:20:36.520
Canada mines a lot of metals.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:38.320
Not necessarily
mercury, but Canada

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:40.861
was a little afraid that this
was going to be a global metals

00:20:40.861 --> 00:20:44.020
treaty and didn't want to
really push for it so much.

00:20:44.020 --> 00:20:46.030
So Canada wasn't pushing.

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:50.930
Australia, again, up and down,
but likes its metals too.

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:55.790
So you didn't have a lot of
developed countries pushing.

00:20:55.790 --> 00:20:59.150
You had some developing country
blocks getting on board.

00:20:59.150 --> 00:21:00.870
So you think about
what countries

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:03.242
and what their different
motivations are.

00:21:03.242 --> 00:21:06.160
And then we get to 2009.

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:09.700
And suddenly in 2009, you have
the European Union still saying

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:11.410
we need a global treaty.

00:21:11.410 --> 00:21:13.130
By then Latin
America's on board.

00:21:13.130 --> 00:21:14.670
We need a global treaty.

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:18.610
And now you have the US saying,
hey, let's not such a bad idea.

00:21:18.610 --> 00:21:19.110
Guess what?

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:21.900
We had a administration change.

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:25.240
One of the things that is
important to note about the US

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:29.890
is that President Obama has
made mercury a pet issue.

00:21:29.890 --> 00:21:32.390
The US-- and I'll talk
about mercury in products

00:21:32.390 --> 00:21:34.500
and how it relates
to the treaty--

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:37.390
has a mercury export ban.

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:44.900
That came in the mid-2000s,
when entry enforcement was

00:21:44.900 --> 00:21:46.280
passed I'm not 100% sure.

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:49.530
But the sponsor of that
legislation in the US Senate

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:51.740
was Senator Obama.

00:21:51.740 --> 00:21:56.500
So he had a interest
in mercury in general.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:22:01.190
And also the US had gone
through about eight or nine

00:22:01.190 --> 00:22:03.850
years of trying to regulate
mercury from coal fired power

00:22:03.850 --> 00:22:08.910
plants under a court order,
under the Clean Air Act,

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:11.260
and had kind of messed
it up under Bush.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:15.499
And when Obama came in,
the clean air mercury rule

00:22:15.499 --> 00:22:17.040
had been thrown out
of court and they

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:19.710
had to go back and do it again.

00:22:19.710 --> 00:22:23.030
And so Obama, being
interested in mercury,

00:22:23.030 --> 00:22:25.470
said let's regulate again.

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:27.470
And the Mercury and
Air Toxic Standards

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:29.440
came in 2012 in the US.

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:30.990
But that was well under way.

00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:34.880
So the US starts saying, hey,
this isn't that bad an idea.

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:37.720
Because if we want to solve our
mercury problem domestically,

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:42.660
we need both international
and domestic action.

00:22:42.660 --> 00:22:45.720
This is kind of a win.

00:22:45.720 --> 00:22:48.840
It's also a political win
because protecting babies

00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:51.170
and not having
mercury in our food

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:55.890
is a kind of clear
public message as well.

00:22:55.890 --> 00:22:56.647
China-- yeah?

00:22:56.647 --> 00:22:58.355
AUDIENCE: Can you
speak a little bit more

00:22:58.355 --> 00:23:03.640
about the cost benefit analysis
and what type of decisions

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:05.472
a politician and
some of these people

00:23:05.472 --> 00:23:12.040
are making to make them more
attractive for this type

00:23:12.040 --> 00:23:12.580
of law?

00:23:12.580 --> 00:23:13.550
NOELLE SELIN: I can't.

00:23:13.550 --> 00:23:16.420
I'm actually doing a lot of work
on that in my group right now.

00:23:16.420 --> 00:23:18.660
So what they did for the
cost benefit analysis

00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:21.580
for the Mercury and
Air Toxic Standards,

00:23:21.580 --> 00:23:24.660
it was a little bit of an end
run around the idea of cost

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:25.480
benefit analysis.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:27.110
Because what they
said was, we're

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:28.534
going to regulate mercury.

00:23:28.534 --> 00:23:30.200
It's going to have
benefits particularly

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:32.260
on sensitive groups.

00:23:32.260 --> 00:23:37.570
So in terms of overall
economic benefits,

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:40.090
it was hard to get
that number up,

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:43.110
in terms of a strict
cost benefit analysis.

00:23:43.110 --> 00:23:45.300
Because the people who
are most harmed by mercury

00:23:45.300 --> 00:23:48.180
are the people like
subsistence fishers,

00:23:48.180 --> 00:23:54.220
who eat a lot of local fish,
particularly for the domestic.

00:23:54.220 --> 00:23:59.860
A lot of general public gets
their fish from cans of tuna

00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:01.816
from the Atlantic, the Pacific.

00:24:01.816 --> 00:24:03.940
That's going to respond to
global emissions and not

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:04.650
local emissions.

00:24:04.650 --> 00:24:07.180
So in the US context where
you have to do a cost benefit

00:24:07.180 --> 00:24:10.590
analysis, they ended up
showing the cost benefit

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:14.215
of-- the Mercury and Air
Toxic Standards passed

00:24:14.215 --> 00:24:15.590
the cost benefit
analysis because

00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:18.890
of the particulate
matter benefits.

00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:21.520
Atmospheric particulate
matter contributes

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:24.540
to cardiovascular impacts,
respiratory impacts.

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:28.510
You can show a lot of
deaths if you reduce it.

00:24:28.510 --> 00:24:30.510
Multiply that by a value
of statistical like you

00:24:30.510 --> 00:24:32.867
paid for almost
anything, and that's

00:24:32.867 --> 00:24:34.950
what they did for Mercury
and Air Toxic Standards.

00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:38.240
Now are group is actually
doing a more thorough benefits

00:24:38.240 --> 00:24:41.480
analysis of the Mercury and Air
Toxic Standards out to 2050.

00:24:41.480 --> 00:24:45.510
And we get some
reasonably big numbers

00:24:45.510 --> 00:24:50.572
because we look at both the
Minamata and the Mercury

00:24:50.572 --> 00:24:52.780
and Air Toxic Standards,
the global and the regional.

00:24:52.780 --> 00:24:55.360
But that work's in
progress right now.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:57.550
But as far as what they
needed for the regulation,

00:24:57.550 --> 00:24:58.430
that's what they did.

00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:01.160
Globally, they didn't really
do a cost benefit analysis.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:05.240
It was we need to regulate
where we're kind of agreed

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:08.160
that this is a problem.

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:09.154
Let's go with it.

00:25:09.154 --> 00:25:11.070
Partly that's because a
lot of other countries

00:25:11.070 --> 00:25:13.530
don't have the tradition
of requiring cost benefit

00:25:13.530 --> 00:25:16.240
analysis that the US does.

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:19.400
So hopefully that
gets to your question.

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:19.900
Yeah.

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:23.100
So again, China--
China is about half

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:25.890
of global emissions
of mercury right now.

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:28.810
China wasn't
particularly thrilled

00:25:28.810 --> 00:25:31.480
about this whole thing.

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:34.770
But China came around.

00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:37.020
Again, the US and the
EU and Latin America,

00:25:37.020 --> 00:25:39.830
you get three major blocks.

00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:42.000
Canada came around, too.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:43.370
Australia came around.

00:25:43.370 --> 00:25:46.920
Africa didn't really
have anything against it.

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:49.380
They probably a net
gain of resources

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:53.090
from this kind of analysis.

00:25:53.090 --> 00:25:57.230
So it's China and India really
who are the most worried

00:25:57.230 --> 00:25:59.145
about what they have to do.

00:25:59.145 --> 00:26:03.290
And in response to
China, it delayed a year

00:26:03.290 --> 00:26:05.060
when negotiations
were going to start.

00:26:05.060 --> 00:26:08.625
So they didn't start till 2010.

00:26:08.625 --> 00:26:10.000
China wanted to
delay them a year

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.020
because China was putting
in its own mercury

00:26:12.020 --> 00:26:15.210
regulations for its power plants
as part of their next five year

00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:15.860
plan.

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:17.530
So China does have
mercury regulations.

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:19.267
They're not
particularly binding.

00:26:19.267 --> 00:26:20.600
They're not particularly strict.

00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:24.840
But they copied Germany's
and said let's put mercury

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:25.766
in our regulations.

00:26:25.766 --> 00:26:27.890
They do you actually have
quite a bit of technology

00:26:27.890 --> 00:26:29.360
on their power plants.

00:26:29.360 --> 00:26:31.330
Whether it's operating
or not is another thing.

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:36.210
But in terms of build out
capacity, they're there.

00:26:36.210 --> 00:26:39.720
So actually negotiating
the instrument

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:42.400
took five negotiating sessions.

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:44.600
It was signed in 2013.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:47.120
Now once an
international agreement

00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:49.060
is signed by
countries, they have

00:26:49.060 --> 00:26:54.960
to go and ratify it, make it
consistent with their US law.

00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:58.530
That in the US usually has
to go through the Senate.

00:26:58.530 --> 00:27:00.380
In this case, it did not.

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:06.370
The US accepted a procedure
equivalent to that

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:08.170
of ratification,
the Mercury Treaty

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:11.100
becoming the first
party because it

00:27:11.100 --> 00:27:15.790
was so consistent with US
law that it essentially

00:27:15.790 --> 00:27:18.360
was an executive decision.

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:20.110
The administration
said, we don't actually

00:27:20.110 --> 00:27:21.400
need to do anything.

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:24.800
It's pretty much an
embodiment of US law.

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:27.130
Because we're doing
so much on mercury,

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:31.720
this does not go much further
than the US already goes.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:34.940
So that's one
particular lesson is

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:38.790
that the US and the EU
in particular, and you

00:27:38.790 --> 00:27:43.570
can see this also in the
reading about the EU,

00:27:43.570 --> 00:27:45.630
these national
laws often are sort

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:49.480
of leading the
international standards.

00:27:49.480 --> 00:27:53.940
So it's actually
predictable in the sense

00:27:53.940 --> 00:27:57.660
that you're not going to get
countries like China, countries

00:27:57.660 --> 00:28:02.220
in Africa, to do the same kinds
of end of pipe expensive power

00:28:02.220 --> 00:28:04.920
plant controls that you
might expect in the US

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:08.610
when they don't even
have the basic controls

00:28:08.610 --> 00:28:11.720
or maybe don't even have
power plants to begin with.

00:28:11.720 --> 00:28:13.830
So again, thinking
about what it's

00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:15.540
sort of a lowest
common denominator

00:28:15.540 --> 00:28:19.270
that you often get in these
international agreements.

00:28:19.270 --> 00:28:25.679
So one emphasis of the
agreement was emissions.

00:28:25.679 --> 00:28:28.220
And I'm not going to talk too
much about emissions given what

00:28:28.220 --> 00:28:30.120
you guys are
interested in-- again,

00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:33.730
that's the power sector
part-- but that was only one

00:28:33.730 --> 00:28:34.660
component of the tree.

00:28:34.660 --> 00:28:38.570
Another is mercury in
products and processes,

00:28:38.570 --> 00:28:41.947
which I think is of probably
more interesting to you guys.

00:28:41.947 --> 00:28:44.030
So I'm going to talk about
products and processes.

00:28:44.030 --> 00:28:46.363
And I'm going to talk about
what they did with artisanal

00:28:46.363 --> 00:28:49.170
and small scale gold mining,
because those both have kind

00:28:49.170 --> 00:28:53.620
of supply chain type issues.

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:59.040
So where do you see mercury
in products and processes?

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:04.260
So one that is pretty
familiar is thermometers.

00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:07.920
So again, phasing out
in places like the US.

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:10.010
You don't see them that often.

00:29:10.010 --> 00:29:15.530
But thermometers, blood
pressure measuring devices,

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:23.340
some of the old
thermostats have mercury.

00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:26.510
So this whole idea of electrical
control and switching,

00:29:26.510 --> 00:29:28.640
measuring and control.

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:30.680
Batteries, older batteries.

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:33.320
Again, phased out in
the US and the EU,

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:39.030
but common elsewhere
sometimes still.

00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:42.700
Lighting.

00:29:42.700 --> 00:29:45.070
Fluorescent lamps.

00:29:45.070 --> 00:29:48.130
Both regular fluorescent
lamps, the tube versions,

00:29:48.130 --> 00:29:50.690
and compact fluorescent lamps.

00:29:50.690 --> 00:29:54.870
So save energy on balance, but
use a small amount of mercury.

00:29:54.870 --> 00:29:57.010
LEDs don't have mercury.

00:29:57.010 --> 00:30:00.630
But again, with people
encouraging more and more

00:30:00.630 --> 00:30:02.955
compact fluorescent and
fluorescent use in lighting

00:30:02.955 --> 00:30:04.830
because of their energy
efficient properties,

00:30:04.830 --> 00:30:08.540
mercury becomes an issue, and
safe disposal becomes an issue.

00:30:11.310 --> 00:30:12.850
The other is your teeth.

00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:13.890
Dental amalgam.

00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:21.470
So again, some countries have
phased out the use of mercury

00:30:21.470 --> 00:30:22.810
in fillings.

00:30:22.810 --> 00:30:24.810
Others don't.

00:30:24.810 --> 00:30:27.110
It's pretty cheap.

00:30:27.110 --> 00:30:32.430
Even in the US, if you
actually go to the dentist

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:33.950
and you need a
filling and they say,

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:35.783
do you want the silver
one or the white one,

00:30:35.783 --> 00:30:38.210
and the white one's a lot
more expensive even here.

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:40.120
So think about if
you're in a developing

00:30:40.120 --> 00:30:42.200
country what your option is.

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:46.490
Your option is probably
no dental care at all,

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:49.360
but the silver filling
is probably much better

00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:52.630
to have-- you save your
tooth-- than the white filling,

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:57.070
the composite, which is much,
much more expensive for you.

00:30:57.070 --> 00:30:59.890
So use of mercury
in dental amalgam

00:30:59.890 --> 00:31:02.840
was, are we going to
keep using it or not?

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:06.030
Again, can be an
environmental issue

00:31:06.030 --> 00:31:09.740
when people get
cremated and get across.

00:31:12.312 --> 00:31:14.020
And then there's a
bunch of other things.

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:19.640
Chloralkali plants-- so use of
mercury in industrial processes

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:25.650
that are phased out in some
cases, but not in others.

00:31:25.650 --> 00:31:29.200
Vinyl chloride monomer,
particularly in China,

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:30.070
mercury is used.

00:31:30.070 --> 00:31:32.950
So you've got a substance
that you think, mercury,

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:36.150
it's a really concrete
thing to regulate.

00:31:36.150 --> 00:31:38.120
But then think about
all these industries

00:31:38.120 --> 00:31:41.020
that you've now involved.

00:31:41.020 --> 00:31:44.220
So you've got a group
sitting in negotiations.

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:47.280
I actually took a group
of 10 graduate students

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:50.260
to the final negotiating
session, which was in Geneva.

00:31:50.260 --> 00:31:54.590
And you've got a group
of maybe 75 people

00:31:54.590 --> 00:31:57.390
in the room,
representatives from all

00:31:57.390 --> 00:31:59.130
the different countries.

00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:01.670
Industry could come
in as observers.

00:32:01.670 --> 00:32:05.160
But again, if you're an
industry that does this,

00:32:05.160 --> 00:32:07.900
think about how
long and how intense

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:10.800
your observation had to be.

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:13.840
You're going to send a person
to every week long meeting

00:32:13.840 --> 00:32:18.240
during five negotiating
sessions through 2010 to 2013,

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:21.940
spending a week in Geneva
each time just to think about,

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.750
if you're in the electrical
control and switching industry,

00:32:24.750 --> 00:32:27.210
to raise their hand every
time electrical control

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:28.690
and switching comes up.

00:32:28.690 --> 00:32:31.470
And they're not really even
allowed to raise their hand,

00:32:31.470 --> 00:32:33.640
because the only people
that are technically

00:32:33.640 --> 00:32:36.490
allowed to talk on the
floor are countries.

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:39.410
So what you can do as
an electrical control

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:41.290
and switching person
is you can go and lobby

00:32:41.290 --> 00:32:42.660
your friendly countries.

00:32:42.660 --> 00:32:46.050
You can put out a poster
in the lobby and say, hey,

00:32:46.050 --> 00:32:48.411
this is how these
regulations would affect us.

00:32:48.411 --> 00:32:50.410
There's probably somebody
next to you that says,

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:52.310
we have the mercury
free version.

00:32:52.310 --> 00:32:53.900
Come buy it.

00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:59.840
And so depending on your
country and where you are,

00:32:59.840 --> 00:33:02.350
this is what it looks like.

00:33:02.350 --> 00:33:06.770
In the products group, it became
a little bit more informal.

00:33:06.770 --> 00:33:11.010
There were companies that
participated in discussions

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:12.760
as observers.

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:16.570
They talked about
thresholds of where mercury

00:33:16.570 --> 00:33:18.720
would be restricted or not.

00:33:18.720 --> 00:33:20.390
And the companies
started saying, well,

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:23.400
there's an alternative
for this, but there's not

00:33:23.400 --> 00:33:25.980
an alternative for this.

00:33:25.980 --> 00:33:28.590
So as you think about
the major categories,

00:33:28.590 --> 00:33:33.140
you have ones that are a
lot in developed countries

00:33:33.140 --> 00:33:35.680
and then ones that are primarily
in developing countries.

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:40.130
And these are things that used
to be in developed countries

00:33:40.130 --> 00:33:44.860
quite a bit but have
often phased out.

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:48.540
So how do you think about
regulating something

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:50.260
internationally?

00:33:50.260 --> 00:33:52.990
Now there was two
different approaches

00:33:52.990 --> 00:33:56.710
and they refer to them as
positive and negative lists,

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:59.570
which is a little bit confusing
because it meant the opposite

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:00.790
of what you might think.

00:34:00.790 --> 00:34:03.280
But the idea is
that you either say,

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:05.750
I'm going to list all these
things that are banned

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:07.460
and you can't use
mercury in them,

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:11.131
or I'm going to ban
mercury in all products

00:34:11.131 --> 00:34:13.380
and I'm going to make a list
of the ones you can still

00:34:13.380 --> 00:34:14.783
use mercury in.

00:34:14.783 --> 00:34:16.699
So the idea of banning
mercury in all products

00:34:16.699 --> 00:34:18.610
was kind of a nonstarter
because, again,

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:20.860
things like compact
fluorescent lamps

00:34:20.860 --> 00:34:26.170
had benefits that were greater
than the cost of mercury.

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:29.300
Actually no one was really
suggesting that you go back

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:35.139
to incandescence because they've
actually done on the assessment

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:40.520
that if you actually have a very
heavy coal load in your power,

00:34:40.520 --> 00:34:43.520
the mercury that you save by
going to a compact fluorescent

00:34:43.520 --> 00:34:47.280
is much larger amounts than
the mercury that's actually

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:48.860
in the light bulb.

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:51.060
And there's a move to
get less and less mercury

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:53.030
in that light bulb.

00:34:53.030 --> 00:34:55.800
So the idea that
they came up with

00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:59.630
was-- there was a
lot of discussion.

00:34:59.630 --> 00:35:01.940
Do you have the blanket
ban with the exceptions?

00:35:01.940 --> 00:35:05.850
Do you just list the ones that
you're phasing out and banning?

00:35:05.850 --> 00:35:07.570
And they came out
the latter approach.

00:35:07.570 --> 00:35:09.070
But then they had
to negotiate which

00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:14.680
of these things on this list was
on there, which was exempted,

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:18.780
and if there were
thresholds to each of these.

00:35:18.780 --> 00:35:22.430
So what kind of level
of mercury would you

00:35:22.430 --> 00:35:26.181
accept in these or not?

00:35:26.181 --> 00:35:26.680
Yes?

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:28.000
AUDIENCE: I'm just
wondering why they

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.320
would go about it
that way trying

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:31.280
to create an exhaustive
list when they don't know

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:33.090
future technology
that's going to come out

00:35:33.090 --> 00:35:35.500
rather than setting
out a set of criteria

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:37.910
that's saying if thee
product meets a, b, and c,

00:35:37.910 --> 00:35:39.026
then you can it?

00:35:39.026 --> 00:35:40.915
NOELLE SELIN: Who decides
on those criteria?

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:48.910
Or actually reviews whether
you actually met those?

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:51.710
And part of that
is transparency.

00:35:51.710 --> 00:35:57.260
So what countries have to do is
then go back to their countries

00:35:57.260 --> 00:35:58.820
and say, what am I allowing?

00:35:58.820 --> 00:35:59.950
What am I not?

00:35:59.950 --> 00:36:03.850
You have to know what you
can put mercury in and not.

00:36:03.850 --> 00:36:06.670
So there's kind of a
transparency approach

00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:08.170
that happens.

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:10.210
I think the two
options that came up,

00:36:10.210 --> 00:36:15.114
the either blanket ban
plus exceptions or the we

00:36:15.114 --> 00:36:16.780
list the things that
they we're banning,

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:21.310
were kind of the two approaches
that they most looked at.

00:36:21.310 --> 00:36:24.294
Because again, that would
make it even more wishy-washy,

00:36:24.294 --> 00:36:26.210
I think, because then
you could show, oh yeah,

00:36:26.210 --> 00:36:29.530
well I fulfilled these
three requirements.

00:36:29.530 --> 00:36:32.010
So that wouldn't
be that stringent

00:36:32.010 --> 00:36:35.380
in international context because
there's no body that can really

00:36:35.380 --> 00:36:36.740
certify those requirements.

00:36:36.740 --> 00:36:39.150
So the key with
international regulation

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:42.120
is that there's no
enforcement essentially.

00:36:46.150 --> 00:36:48.480
It's an environmental treaty.

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:52.660
You can barely enforce the ones
that actually involve weapons.

00:36:52.660 --> 00:36:56.050
You're not going to
go bomb someone that

00:36:56.050 --> 00:36:57.540
is using too much mercury.

00:36:57.540 --> 00:36:59.582
What's going to happen
is you're going to say,

00:36:59.582 --> 00:37:01.040
hey, you're using
too much mercury.

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:03.630
We're going to caution you.

00:37:03.630 --> 00:37:06.560
We're going to shame you in
the international context.

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:09.062
We're not going to let you vote.

00:37:09.062 --> 00:37:10.770
Maybe we'll actually
give you more money,

00:37:10.770 --> 00:37:12.860
because probably the
reason you're not complying

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:15.526
is because you can't afford it.

00:37:15.526 --> 00:37:16.650
That's what really happens.

00:37:16.650 --> 00:37:17.880
Yeah?

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:18.860
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

