00:40:07.790 --> 00:40:10.310
which I'll talk about next.

00:40:10.310 --> 00:40:15.950
But yeah, the idea is that
you can do awareness raising

00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:17.370
workshops.

00:40:17.370 --> 00:40:19.710
So they bring in
international experts,

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:23.080
national experts, talk about
the damages of mercury,

00:40:23.080 --> 00:40:27.240
talk about what you could
potentially be doing about it.

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:29.220
That's sort of where
the state of art

00:40:29.220 --> 00:40:30.880
is, I think, at this point.

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:37.390
But yeah, so you had to go
through these major categories

00:40:37.390 --> 00:40:39.530
of mercury use.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:43.780
And then I just want to flip
ahead a little bit to actually

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:45.970
what happened.

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:48.850
Again, you have different
phase outs and phase downs.

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:54.340
And then there's this very
legalese exemption period

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:57.190
where you can have
either general exemptions

00:40:57.190 --> 00:40:59.040
or specific exemptions.

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:02.940
Another area where mercury
was generalized exemption

00:41:02.940 --> 00:41:07.110
was mercury used as a
preservative in vaccines.

00:41:07.110 --> 00:41:10.550
So that was one that, again,
this sort of cost benefit

00:41:10.550 --> 00:41:14.710
analysis-- there's no
evidence that it's harmful.

00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:16.550
Again, other than the
general sense that we

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:19.190
want to phase down mercury.

00:41:19.190 --> 00:41:22.990
But it's been phased out
for precautionary reasons

00:41:22.990 --> 00:41:25.580
and also because,
again, don't want

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:28.950
to use too much mercury
in developed countries.

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:31.260
But what happens is in
developing countries,

00:41:31.260 --> 00:41:35.980
you have vaccines that it means
it doesn't need refrigeration

00:41:35.980 --> 00:41:38.310
if you use a mercury
containing preservative.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:39.820
So again, you're
getting vaccines

00:41:39.820 --> 00:41:43.610
to places where you don't have
refrigeration if you use it.

00:41:43.610 --> 00:41:47.906
So that's why that ended
up in a general exemption.

00:41:47.906 --> 00:41:50.380
AUDIENCE: I do go
through this process.

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:56.170
And when does the science
get into the discussion.

00:41:56.170 --> 00:42:00.160
Because you have at some
point to decide [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:02.650
They know exactly what
levels to be allowed

00:42:02.650 --> 00:42:05.170
and they want to
just being reflected.

00:42:05.170 --> 00:42:08.154
So I'm wondering where
does this get in.

00:42:08.154 --> 00:42:10.570
NOELLE SELIN: It's a lot less
technical than you think is.

00:42:10.570 --> 00:42:13.830
So where the scientific
analysis came in

00:42:13.830 --> 00:42:17.280
was really in that global
mercury assessment 2002

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:18.700
and the updates of that.

00:42:18.700 --> 00:42:20.590
And then the
negotiator said, yeah,

00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:24.500
the scientific case is made
that we ought to reduce mercury.

00:42:24.500 --> 00:42:29.260
There is no particular substance
by substance sense of when they

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:31.310
actually thought to phase out.

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:35.850
No one did an analysis of what
the benefits of phasing out in

00:42:35.850 --> 00:42:39.050
switches and relays versus
linear fluorescent lamps.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:42.410
That just wasn't even
on the radar screen.

00:42:42.410 --> 00:42:46.230
There were assessments that
said where are the sources?

00:42:46.230 --> 00:42:48.460
Where does mercury go?

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:51.266
But then it was really a
horse trading kind of thing.

00:42:51.266 --> 00:42:52.640
I'll give you
switches and relays

00:42:52.640 --> 00:42:54.230
if you give me cosmetics.

00:42:54.230 --> 00:42:57.050
Because each country
wants to sort of

00:42:57.050 --> 00:43:00.870
protect its own interests there.

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:03.870
Some might have mercury
free alternatives

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:07.030
that they might want to sell.

00:43:07.030 --> 00:43:10.190
Others it might be a
particularly pressing issue,

00:43:10.190 --> 00:43:12.600
like this cosmetics.

00:43:12.600 --> 00:43:15.070
It might be a particular
public health issue

00:43:15.070 --> 00:43:17.680
in countries and in regions.

00:43:17.680 --> 00:43:22.320
Mercury is a component
of some skin lightening

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:27.870
creams which have been--
people have tried to ban them.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:31.820
But again, countries with less
of a regulatory infrastructure,

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:35.830
it actually-- again,
putting mercury directly

00:43:35.830 --> 00:43:41.350
on your skin, not a good idea,
and can be a big public health

00:43:41.350 --> 00:43:43.440
problem in some
communities where there's

00:43:43.440 --> 00:43:50.420
an interest in using these
things culturally and also

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:53.170
in cultural practices,
like use of mercury

00:43:53.170 --> 00:43:59.480
in religious types of practices
that can be dangerous.

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:04.650
So those cosmetics again,
greater than one PPM.

00:44:04.650 --> 00:44:07.810
Also topical antiseptics,
pesticides, biocides,

00:44:07.810 --> 00:44:13.140
that kind of thing, use mercury
to toxic kill the bacteria.

00:44:13.140 --> 00:44:15.430
There's other ways to do that.

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:20.210
But again, in countries where
you can't really control import

00:44:20.210 --> 00:44:23.690
very well in terms
of your capacity,

00:44:23.690 --> 00:44:26.400
international
regulation can be an end

00:44:26.400 --> 00:44:29.050
run around that to think about.

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:35.360
And again, for dental amalgam
there was a goal of phase down.

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:36.810
But again, no set date.

00:44:36.810 --> 00:44:39.270
So to the extent
that you can, use

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:42.060
the more expensive but more
environmentally friendly

00:44:42.060 --> 00:44:42.960
alternatives.

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:45.210
And that actually ends up
getting into the environment

00:44:45.210 --> 00:44:46.840
quite a bit.

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:50.907
Story in Massachusetts when
they required dental separators

00:44:50.907 --> 00:44:53.240
in dental offices-- it used
to be that they just flushed

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:55.610
the stuff down the drain when
they changed your filing--

00:44:55.610 --> 00:44:57.594
they required dental
amalgam separators.

00:44:57.594 --> 00:44:59.010
You can actually
look at that date

00:44:59.010 --> 00:45:00.570
and look at the
mercury level in fish

00:45:00.570 --> 00:45:02.313
in the waterways
of Massachusetts

00:45:02.313 --> 00:45:05.280
and it goes dramatically
down right after that.

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:08.960
It actually does wash
right into the waterways.

00:45:08.960 --> 00:45:15.094
Again, it's a lot of mercury
that's in a particular filling.

00:45:15.094 --> 00:45:15.594
Yeah?

00:45:15.594 --> 00:45:17.844
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:17.844 --> 00:45:19.510
When they pick a date
to phase this out,

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:24.390
2020, is this just sounds
good or is there some--

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:27.100
NOELLE SELIN: It
just sounds good.

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:29.300
AUDIENCE: Let's make
it far, far, far away.

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:31.030
Not next year, not two years.

00:45:31.030 --> 00:45:31.704
Something that--

00:45:31.704 --> 00:45:33.120
NOELLE SELIN: And
it's negotiated.

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:38.220
So people that want--
again, a lot of these things

00:45:38.220 --> 00:45:40.020
are phased out in Europe.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:43.520
And so the companies have
figured out a way around them.

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:48.380
Europe has an interest in
getting these things globalized

00:45:48.380 --> 00:45:50.850
because they have very
strict regulations like we

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:54.010
and like rows that
talk about what

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:56.290
you need to sell
products in Europe.

00:45:56.290 --> 00:45:59.920
And to the extent that
becomes a global regulation,

00:45:59.920 --> 00:46:04.060
that obviously favors-- Europe
thinks it's the right thing

00:46:04.060 --> 00:46:06.070
to do, first of all.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:08.830
But also it makes
it a global standard

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:12.160
as opposed to different
standards throughout the world.

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:15.100
So you've got European
countries often

00:46:15.100 --> 00:46:17.150
pushing for earlier
and earlier phase outs.

00:46:17.150 --> 00:46:21.650
Now maybe China for example,
which actually produces

00:46:21.650 --> 00:46:24.430
a lot of these compact
fluorescent lamps,

00:46:24.430 --> 00:46:28.060
probably wants later
phase in dates.

00:46:28.060 --> 00:46:31.220
So 2020 emerges as a compromise.

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:34.280
Again, thinking about the
timing of actually entering

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:38.390
into force for a treaty, I think
you need 50 parties ratifying.

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:40.900
US ratified really, really
quickly, because again,

00:46:40.900 --> 00:46:43.490
it just said rubber stamped it.

00:46:43.490 --> 00:46:45.690
It's the only country
to ratify so far.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:53.990
So conservatively at least 2015
before it enters into force.

00:46:53.990 --> 00:46:57.730
So setting a day before
that would be kind of weird.

00:46:57.730 --> 00:46:59.760
So yeah, you have
to phase it out

00:46:59.760 --> 00:47:03.020
before you actually signed it.

00:47:03.020 --> 00:47:08.660
So 2020 is a relatively
early date in this area.

00:47:08.660 --> 00:47:13.800
Mercury mining is phased
out also under the treaty,

00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:16.080
and it's 2035.

00:47:16.080 --> 00:47:21.390
Or no-- I think it's
15 years after entry

00:47:21.390 --> 00:47:24.240
into force for that particular
country or something like that.

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:28.920
So it can be quite a long time.

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:35.190
So going back a little bit
talking about mercury trade--

00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:38.220
so this just gives you a sense
of where mercury is flowing

00:47:38.220 --> 00:47:41.650
and where it's going--
again, since we've

00:47:41.650 --> 00:47:44.090
had the mercury export ban act.

00:47:44.090 --> 00:47:46.130
But this is actually just
of commodity mercury.

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:48.940
So this isn't
mercury in products.

00:47:48.940 --> 00:47:53.740
So the compact fluorescent
bulbs that we import from China

00:47:53.740 --> 00:47:58.430
are not included in these flows.

00:47:58.430 --> 00:48:00.810
Yet primary mercury
mining in Kurdistan,

00:48:00.810 --> 00:48:04.040
they're actually closing
their mine partly because

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:05.985
of US assistance.

00:48:08.520 --> 00:48:13.370
China has no interest in
actually closing their mine,

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:17.110
although they will have to under
the treaty if they ratify it.

00:48:17.110 --> 00:48:20.980
But China's mostly using itself.

00:48:20.980 --> 00:48:24.570
So the mercury that
gets used in products--

00:48:24.570 --> 00:48:29.030
so you don't see much of an
arrow there coming out of China

00:48:29.030 --> 00:48:32.390
because it's not
internationally traded.

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:35.250
But again, a lot of flows
for a lot of this mercury

00:48:35.250 --> 00:48:39.390
is coming from recycled mercury,
mercury stocks, mercury in use.

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:41.764
So you've got mercury
flowing as mercury,

00:48:41.764 --> 00:48:43.430
then getting incorporated
into products.

00:48:43.430 --> 00:48:46.995
You get obviously the trade
in products, and then trade

00:48:46.995 --> 00:48:48.800
in wastes.

00:48:48.800 --> 00:48:55.290
So once the product is no longer
useful, what do you do with it?

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:58.190
I said that the mercury is a
full life cycle convention.

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:00.640
It does is actually
sort of yield

00:49:00.640 --> 00:49:03.260
a lot of the waste issues
to the Basel Convention,

00:49:03.260 --> 00:49:07.170
which deals with
wastes internationally.

00:49:07.170 --> 00:49:12.060
So it has sound guidelines
of trans-boundary movements

00:49:12.060 --> 00:49:13.300
of hazardous waste.

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:15.990
And that pretty much
covers the mercury.

00:49:15.990 --> 00:49:17.960
So they tried to
make that consistent.

00:49:17.960 --> 00:49:22.580
Problem is that it doesn't
have the same set of parties.

00:49:22.580 --> 00:49:25.790
In particular, the US is not
party to the Basel Convention.

00:49:25.790 --> 00:49:29.680
But pretty much does
the required things

00:49:29.680 --> 00:49:32.570
that the Basel Convention
does in the sense

00:49:32.570 --> 00:49:35.940
of being able to deal
with hazardous waste

00:49:35.940 --> 00:49:36.980
in a reasonable way.

00:49:38.956 --> 00:49:45.075
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] if they
cut off the influx of mercury

00:49:45.075 --> 00:49:47.158
then they will only be
stuck with trying to manage

00:49:47.158 --> 00:49:48.778
their own creation of mercury?

00:49:48.778 --> 00:49:49.720
NOELLE SELIN: Right.

00:49:49.720 --> 00:49:55.620
And to the extent that
they actually use mercury--

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:59.980
I'm not sure exactly what
the use of mercury will be.

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:05.010
But again, trade is
restricted under the treaty.

00:50:05.010 --> 00:50:06.330
US already has an export ban.

00:50:06.330 --> 00:50:09.330
EU has an export ban.

00:50:09.330 --> 00:50:12.680
Mercury trade will only be
allowed for exempted uses.

00:50:12.680 --> 00:50:14.430
So if you're making
one of those exemption

00:50:14.430 --> 00:50:19.570
processes like dental amalgam--
that might be Australia.

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:21.650
It might just be
importing for teeth.

00:50:21.650 --> 00:50:22.680
Who knows?

00:50:22.680 --> 00:50:25.590
But again, if you're using it
for an exempted use, it's OK.

00:50:25.590 --> 00:50:27.550
If you're not, it's not.

00:50:27.550 --> 00:50:30.280
And that sort of actually
is a really good segue

00:50:30.280 --> 00:50:33.340
into the artisanal and
small gold mining story.

00:50:33.340 --> 00:50:35.940
Because again, thinking
about where mercury goes

00:50:35.940 --> 00:50:39.910
and where mercury is in trade,
artisanal small scale gold

00:50:39.910 --> 00:50:43.980
mining is a really big deal in a
lot of countries, big emission.

00:50:43.980 --> 00:50:47.610
But the question is, how
do they get their mercury?

00:50:47.610 --> 00:50:51.100
You're a small scale gold
miner in a developing country.

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:57.430
You need to buy mercury to
figure out how you actually

00:50:57.430 --> 00:51:00.370
mine your gold.

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:03.800
So this is a figure
from a paper that

00:51:03.800 --> 00:51:07.030
looks at what the artisanal
and small scale gold mining

00:51:07.030 --> 00:51:09.700
process is and how that relates
to the gold supply chain, which

00:51:09.700 --> 00:51:11.533
I thought would be
interesting for you guys.

00:51:11.533 --> 00:51:16.177
So you started at the top with
mercury exporting countries.

00:51:16.177 --> 00:51:17.760
And a lot of those
exporting countries

00:51:17.760 --> 00:51:20.190
think they're
exporting to dentists.

00:51:20.190 --> 00:51:23.710
So one of my colleagues works in
the artisanal small scale gold

00:51:23.710 --> 00:51:26.280
mining area and he
showed this picture

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:30.010
of an artisanal small scale
gold mining community.

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:33.850
And it was mercury dental shop.

00:51:33.850 --> 00:51:35.450
Like yeah, right.

00:51:35.450 --> 00:51:36.770
You're a mercury dental shop.

00:51:36.770 --> 00:51:38.830
You're in a gold
mining community.

00:51:38.830 --> 00:51:41.390
But in a lot of cases,
they'll buy mercury

00:51:41.390 --> 00:51:45.230
from dentists or
a dental middleman

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:48.612
and actually sell
illegally to the miners.

00:51:48.612 --> 00:51:50.570
So then you're the miner,
and miners over here,

00:51:50.570 --> 00:51:51.900
they dig your pit.

00:51:51.900 --> 00:51:53.820
You get the ore.

00:51:53.820 --> 00:51:56.760
And then mix it altogether.

00:51:56.760 --> 00:51:58.820
So then what you're
left with is you're

00:51:58.820 --> 00:52:02.350
left with some mercury
amalgamated with gold.

00:52:02.350 --> 00:52:05.600
And you've got some waste.

00:52:05.600 --> 00:52:08.122
And that's where you
have this amalgam ball

00:52:08.122 --> 00:52:09.080
and you have the waste.

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:10.740
Now the waste is going
to have some rock in it,

00:52:10.740 --> 00:52:11.870
it's going to have
some water, it's

00:52:11.870 --> 00:52:13.619
probably going to have
some mercury in it,

00:52:13.619 --> 00:52:17.522
because you couldn't get all
of it to stick to the gold.

00:52:17.522 --> 00:52:18.730
And what do you do with that?

00:52:18.730 --> 00:52:20.850
You just dump that.

00:52:20.850 --> 00:52:24.870
So you release mercury
laden byproduct

00:52:24.870 --> 00:52:27.860
into the waterways, which
could have local impacts.

00:52:27.860 --> 00:52:30.870
But probably not going
to enter the global pool.

00:52:30.870 --> 00:52:34.040
Because again, you just rinsed
it out into your local place.

00:52:34.040 --> 00:52:35.380
It might.

00:52:35.380 --> 00:52:37.210
We don't know the
science on that.

00:52:37.210 --> 00:52:39.760
But you've got
amalgam ball, which is

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:42.860
must your money, with your gold.

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:45.500
But it's bound up
with the mercury.

00:52:45.500 --> 00:52:47.506
So what do you do?

00:52:47.506 --> 00:52:50.860
You can do a couple of things.

00:52:50.860 --> 00:52:53.520
You can burn it yourself.

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:58.680
So this would be
the artisanal part.

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:01.170
You're actually going
to just get a pan,

00:53:01.170 --> 00:53:03.215
you're going to light
a fire under it,

00:53:03.215 --> 00:53:05.110
and you're going to let
the mercury burn off.

00:53:05.110 --> 00:53:07.200
Now that's not
particularly efficient,

00:53:07.200 --> 00:53:10.110
but it's probably the cheapest
way you're going to do it.

00:53:10.110 --> 00:53:12.980
Now one of the ways to
minimize the mercury loss

00:53:12.980 --> 00:53:14.750
is to have a retort.

00:53:14.750 --> 00:53:16.670
So basically you have
a little cap on it.

00:53:19.727 --> 00:53:22.060
The mercury condenses and
then you drip the mercury back

00:53:22.060 --> 00:53:23.160
into a little cup.

00:53:23.160 --> 00:53:24.530
You could use the mercury again.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:25.920
It saves it from going
into the atmosphere.

00:53:25.920 --> 00:53:27.270
It also saves you
some money because you

00:53:27.270 --> 00:53:29.120
don't have to go back
and buy more mercury,

00:53:29.120 --> 00:53:30.509
or buy less of it.

00:53:30.509 --> 00:53:32.050
So that's been one
of the things that

00:53:32.050 --> 00:53:35.770
has come up in trying to
minimize the mercury lost.

00:53:35.770 --> 00:53:37.614
But again, as you
think about it,

00:53:37.614 --> 00:53:39.530
not the most healthy
place in the world to be,

00:53:39.530 --> 00:53:45.860
breathing over a
burning mercury pit.

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:50.000
Again, lots of local issues.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:57.060
So you've got this AGSM product.

00:53:57.060 --> 00:54:01.430
Sometimes that burning can
happen in local shops as well.

00:54:01.430 --> 00:54:02.650
That's more of a small scale.

00:54:02.650 --> 00:54:05.520
So you take your amalgam
ball to your local shop.

00:54:05.520 --> 00:54:06.770
More efficient.

00:54:06.770 --> 00:54:08.020
That guy's going to get a cut.

00:54:08.020 --> 00:54:11.420
So you think about that
depending on the community.

00:54:11.420 --> 00:54:13.860
That might happen.

00:54:13.860 --> 00:54:18.740
Usually a buyer, who can
double as a mercury dealer,

00:54:18.740 --> 00:54:23.460
buys that intermediate gold
product, does a final burning

00:54:23.460 --> 00:54:26.170
step that makes
it more pure gold,

00:54:26.170 --> 00:54:30.670
then you enter the
regular gold supply chain.

00:54:30.670 --> 00:54:34.930
And you end up with, on
the market, about up to 30%

00:54:34.930 --> 00:54:37.720
of artisanal and small
scale gold mining gold

00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:41.530
that then goes to a combination
of jewelry and investors

00:54:41.530 --> 00:54:43.550
in industry.

00:54:43.550 --> 00:54:48.700
So it really is not a
insignificant amount

00:54:48.700 --> 00:54:54.190
of gold on the market that
comes out of this process

00:54:54.190 --> 00:54:55.800
and involves mercury.

00:54:55.800 --> 00:54:58.870
So again, with the
price of gold the way

00:54:58.870 --> 00:55:01.510
it is, this is
something that has

00:55:01.510 --> 00:55:05.200
a lot of influence on
the livelihood of people

00:55:05.200 --> 00:55:07.270
who are involved in this.

00:55:07.270 --> 00:55:09.570
So it's a development issue.

00:55:09.570 --> 00:55:12.000
It's a local community issue.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:13.890
It's also an international
market issue.

00:55:16.870 --> 00:55:21.030
So there's a lot of
different certifications

00:55:21.030 --> 00:55:24.220
that come into gold,
some of which--

00:55:24.220 --> 00:55:26.383
at least one, I forget
the-- I don't have it

00:55:26.383 --> 00:55:29.560
in my notes, the
particular ones.

00:55:29.560 --> 00:55:33.950
But one of which does
incorporate mercury

00:55:33.950 --> 00:55:37.950
into the certification
standards and one doesn't.

00:55:37.950 --> 00:55:40.640
So there's a difference in--
there's a couple of different,

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:42.840
like fair trade,
fair mine, the talk

00:55:42.840 --> 00:55:47.420
about the conditions of the
miners and various things.

00:55:47.420 --> 00:55:50.320
Whether or not-- and
how-- they cover mercury

00:55:50.320 --> 00:55:52.450
is an open question.

00:55:52.450 --> 00:55:55.330
So will that help if you
have more of a certification

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:56.410
process?

00:55:56.410 --> 00:55:57.220
Not sure.

00:55:57.220 --> 00:56:00.660
Now how does the
treaty deal with this?

00:56:00.660 --> 00:56:02.960
Well, it has a
number of provisions

00:56:02.960 --> 00:56:08.960
that really boil down to
essentially capacity building,

00:56:08.960 --> 00:56:12.430
suggests that to the extent
possible these sectors be

00:56:12.430 --> 00:56:16.260
regulated and sort
of formalized,

00:56:16.260 --> 00:56:18.160
because they're often
informal sectors.

00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:23.330
Again, illegal mercury, black
market mercury essentially,

00:56:23.330 --> 00:56:26.780
that's from dentists.

00:56:26.780 --> 00:56:29.710
The types of
technologies that can

00:56:29.710 --> 00:56:32.930
prevent the releases of mercury
and make it a little safer

00:56:32.930 --> 00:56:36.950
be adopted in a more
widespread basis.

00:56:36.950 --> 00:56:40.420
But again, it's not eliminating
artisanal small scale

00:56:40.420 --> 00:56:43.680
gold mining because that is a
livelihood for a lot of people.

00:56:43.680 --> 00:56:47.670
It's trying to make it less
mercury dependent and less

00:56:47.670 --> 00:56:51.410
toxic, both for the miners
and for the environment.

00:56:51.410 --> 00:56:56.480
So they've basically estimated
that they could probably

00:56:56.480 --> 00:57:01.140
have the amount of mercury
based on these estimates.

00:57:01.140 --> 00:57:04.100
So there's a lot of opportunity
for reductions, again,

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:08.950
because a lot of these processes
are really inefficient.

00:57:08.950 --> 00:57:11.320
So I want to just
end with talking

00:57:11.320 --> 00:57:16.360
about sort of the
general context

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:19.340
in which this mercury
regulation is happening,

00:57:19.340 --> 00:57:24.670
which is the overall
international regulations

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:27.750
and what's happening globally.

00:57:27.750 --> 00:57:32.570
Because obviously these
producers and people

00:57:32.570 --> 00:57:34.845
who are dealing with
mercury related issues

00:57:34.845 --> 00:57:37.470
aren't just dealing with this as
an international environmental

00:57:37.470 --> 00:57:38.450
issue.

00:57:38.450 --> 00:57:43.310
There might be other chemicals,
other different kinds

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:44.210
of considerations.

00:57:44.210 --> 00:57:47.860
So this is a figure
that one of my students

00:57:47.860 --> 00:57:52.937
put together after going
through the negotiations of all

00:57:52.937 --> 00:57:55.020
the different international
organizations that had

00:57:55.020 --> 00:57:57.400
a roll in the mercury treaty.

00:57:57.400 --> 00:58:02.220
And one really obvious link is
through the existing chemical

00:58:02.220 --> 00:58:04.520
treaties and institutions.

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:06.200
So the Stockholm
Convention is on

00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:07.560
persistent organic pollutants.

00:58:07.560 --> 00:58:12.140
So a lot of pesticides-- DTP,
PCB, industrial chemicals

00:58:12.140 --> 00:58:15.410
like PCBs, also regulating
dioxins and furans

00:58:15.410 --> 00:58:16.470
internationally.

00:58:16.470 --> 00:58:20.770
The Rotterdam Convention is on
trade in hazardous chemicals.

00:58:20.770 --> 00:58:22.440
It's a prior informed
consent provision,

00:58:22.440 --> 00:58:26.000
so it mandates
that countries that

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:28.200
are taking imports of
hazardous chemicals

00:58:28.200 --> 00:58:33.590
must give their informed consent
prior to that chemical being

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:34.280
exported.

00:58:34.280 --> 00:58:37.330
This is trying to prevent
the idea of something's

00:58:37.330 --> 00:58:38.240
banned in the US.

00:58:38.240 --> 00:58:43.390
The US decides you
guys will take it,

00:58:43.390 --> 00:58:45.480
so let's just export it to you.

00:58:45.480 --> 00:58:48.550
The idea is it shifts the
burden to the exporting country

00:58:48.550 --> 00:58:51.300
to make sure that that country
knows what it's getting

00:58:51.300 --> 00:58:53.470
and knows that you
think it's dangerous.

00:58:53.470 --> 00:58:56.450
So there's a list of
chemicals on that convention.

00:58:56.450 --> 00:58:58.620
Again, that's similar to
the prior informed consent

00:58:58.620 --> 00:59:00.430
process that's in the
Basel Convention that

00:59:00.430 --> 00:59:02.129
deals with wastes.

00:59:02.129 --> 00:59:03.920
So again, there's
potential synergies there

00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:07.130
because Rotterdam
and Basel also have

00:59:07.130 --> 00:59:09.070
things potentially
containing mercury

00:59:09.070 --> 00:59:13.150
and also this issue of trade.

00:59:13.150 --> 00:59:16.590
Funding often comes from the
Global Environment Facility,

00:59:16.590 --> 00:59:20.052
which is basically donations
from the rich countries.

00:59:20.052 --> 00:59:21.760
Minamata Convention
has an additional new

00:59:21.760 --> 00:59:23.610
designed specific
funding mechanism

00:59:23.610 --> 00:59:26.400
to be negotiated fully.

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:29.719
But that has to do with issues
that developing countries

00:59:29.719 --> 00:59:32.010
in particular have with the
Global Environment Facility

00:59:32.010 --> 00:59:33.370
and its responsiveness.

00:59:33.370 --> 00:59:38.250
So that was negotiated as
kind of a hybrid compromise.

00:59:38.250 --> 00:59:41.710
Possibly some
multilateral funds that

00:59:41.710 --> 00:59:45.810
actually influence other
environmental negotiations.

00:59:45.810 --> 00:59:48.960
But you have a bunch of other
international organizations

00:59:48.960 --> 00:59:53.180
like World Health Organization
that sets guidance

00:59:53.180 --> 00:59:56.420
for mercury levels
in fish and also

00:59:56.420 --> 00:59:59.800
is involved in
the vaccine thing,

00:59:59.800 --> 01:00:01.650
related to the dental thing.

01:00:01.650 --> 01:00:05.970
So thinking about connections
with that because you

01:00:05.970 --> 01:00:09.340
get very health relevant issue.

01:00:09.340 --> 01:00:11.310
International Labour
Organization--

01:00:11.310 --> 01:00:15.880
obviously in
particular the miners,

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:20.580
and what people are exposed
to in particular factories is

01:00:20.580 --> 01:00:22.800
often in ILO.

01:00:22.800 --> 01:00:24.800
Food and Agriculture
Organization, to the center

01:00:24.800 --> 01:00:26.980
that involves pesticides.

01:00:26.980 --> 01:00:29.330
That's one that comes up.

01:00:29.330 --> 01:00:31.960
So that's the
international bits.

01:00:31.960 --> 01:00:35.440
You've also got a bunch
of guiding principles that

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:35.940
come out.

01:00:35.940 --> 01:00:37.390
The idea that you
can do whatever

01:00:37.390 --> 01:00:39.156
you want to your own
environment but you

01:00:39.156 --> 01:00:40.780
have to watch out
with others comes out

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:41.738
of the Rio Declaration.

01:00:41.738 --> 01:00:43.090
That's 1992.

01:00:43.090 --> 01:00:47.190
There's the general discussions
over a sustainable development.

01:00:47.190 --> 01:00:49.290
These all kind of
inform in a general way

01:00:49.290 --> 01:00:51.180
the kinds of regulations
that are developed

01:00:51.180 --> 01:00:53.685
under the Minamata Convention.

01:00:53.685 --> 01:00:55.310
Things like the
precautionary principle

01:00:55.310 --> 01:00:58.260
come out of these principles.

01:00:58.260 --> 01:01:01.330
And then, of course, you have
multilateral regulations--

01:01:01.330 --> 01:01:04.330
domestic agreements,
bilateral agreements,

01:01:04.330 --> 01:01:07.700
regional agreement--
that are also

01:01:07.700 --> 01:01:11.030
dealing with mercury
but on different levels

01:01:11.030 --> 01:01:13.540
and among different
countries that may or may not

01:01:13.540 --> 01:01:15.820
be consistent or not.

01:01:15.820 --> 01:01:18.570
Again, domestic
governments try to make

01:01:18.570 --> 01:01:20.850
it as consistent as possible
in the negotiations.

01:01:20.850 --> 01:01:24.330
But everyone's
trying to do that,

01:01:24.330 --> 01:01:26.950
so it might not be possible.

01:01:26.950 --> 01:01:31.400
So that's all I had
for prepared slides.

01:01:31.400 --> 01:01:34.470
I was told to keep it to about
an hour-- I think I made it--

01:01:34.470 --> 01:01:36.600
and open up for
discussion after that.

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:38.660
AUDIENCE: I was
just wondering what

01:01:38.660 --> 01:01:42.540
happens to mercury
once whoever's doing

01:01:42.540 --> 01:01:44.440
the proper disposal gets it.

01:01:44.440 --> 01:01:46.197
Do they convert it to
some safe chemical?

01:01:46.197 --> 01:01:48.780
Do they put it barrels and bury
it under a mountain in Nevada?

01:01:48.780 --> 01:01:50.290
NOELLE SELIN: The latter.

01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:52.791
Mercury's an element.

01:01:52.791 --> 01:01:53.790
You can't get rid of it.

01:01:53.790 --> 01:01:57.330
So not much you can do about it.

01:01:57.330 --> 01:02:00.870
The nice thing is, the
quantities are pretty small.

01:02:00.870 --> 01:02:04.730
So again, encapsulating
it, burying it barrels

01:02:04.730 --> 01:02:09.000
is pretty much what
you want to do with it.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:12.250
Again, you're talking
about tons per year.

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:15.330
When you're talking about
carbon it's gigatons per year.

01:02:15.330 --> 01:02:17.360
Mercury is in actual
tons per year.

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:18.780
And mercury is pretty dense.

01:02:18.780 --> 01:02:23.785
So this is also why your
clump of mercury in your tooth

01:02:23.785 --> 01:02:26.640
or in the thermometer is
actually pretty significant,

01:02:26.640 --> 01:02:32.300
because there's a lot of
mercury there in comparison

01:02:32.300 --> 01:02:35.710
to the global budget,
whereas the amount of carbon

01:02:35.710 --> 01:02:36.720
is teeny tiny.

01:02:40.580 --> 01:02:43.151
But yeah, I'm not sure
about Nevada specifically.

01:02:43.151 --> 01:02:44.400
You could put it in a trailer.

01:02:44.400 --> 01:02:46.180
I've seen mercury trailers.

01:02:46.180 --> 01:02:49.109
The strategic mercury stockpile
was in trailers for a while.

01:02:49.109 --> 01:02:50.400
AUDIENCE: Sounds pretty secure.

01:02:54.220 --> 01:03:00.010
So do you see a company
that you thought

01:03:00.010 --> 01:03:04.060
was doing something right,
in terms of understanding

01:03:04.060 --> 01:03:06.370
the role that they could play?

01:03:06.370 --> 01:03:08.880
Because this seems
pretty out of my hands.

01:03:08.880 --> 01:03:10.780
So as a company at
the end of the day,

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:11.950
there's nothing I can do.

01:03:11.950 --> 01:03:16.120
I just probably can go
to local state official,

01:03:16.120 --> 01:03:19.420
voice my concerns,
hopefully get him elected,

01:03:19.420 --> 01:03:22.145
and let the whole
thing just kind of--

01:03:22.145 --> 01:03:24.340
NOELLE SELIN: There were
definitely companies

01:03:24.340 --> 01:03:28.910
involved, but in a limited way.

01:03:28.910 --> 01:03:32.080
The lighting manufacturers
were there a lot.

01:03:32.080 --> 01:03:34.930
But mainly I saw them
talk about their products

01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:38.900
and their minimization and
really kind of get the message

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:41.580
that we are trying to take the
mercury out of our lighting

01:03:41.580 --> 01:03:45.930
and we're doing a good
job, so don't ban us.

01:03:45.930 --> 01:03:49.340
And I think to that
extent there was

01:03:49.340 --> 01:03:52.020
a lot of awareness
raising of technologies

01:03:52.020 --> 01:03:55.170
and available technologies
that was done by companies

01:03:55.170 --> 01:03:58.060
in these international fora.

01:03:58.060 --> 01:04:02.780
Again, it's an
opportunity to trumpet

01:04:02.780 --> 01:04:06.010
your green technologies.

01:04:06.010 --> 01:04:10.660
So that would be sort of the
positive end of companies

01:04:10.660 --> 01:04:13.750
advocating-- mercury free
alternative companies,

01:04:13.750 --> 01:04:14.490
definitely.

01:04:14.490 --> 01:04:16.950
If you had a
mercury-free something,

01:04:16.950 --> 01:04:21.000
you definitely were
waving the flag for it.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:23.300
There were other
companies that were there

01:04:23.300 --> 01:04:27.460
to make sure that their
interests were protected.

01:04:27.460 --> 01:04:29.200
Oil and gas.

01:04:29.200 --> 01:04:32.230
Mercury is a small
contaminant in oil and gas.

01:04:32.230 --> 01:04:35.820
Mercury is mostly
a concern on site.

01:04:35.820 --> 01:04:40.460
So because of the way oil is
distilled in the final product,

01:04:40.460 --> 01:04:41.880
there's not of mercury.

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:49.610
If you have the
unfortunate location

01:04:49.610 --> 01:04:52.930
of being near a mercury deposit
when you're drilling your oil,

01:04:52.930 --> 01:04:54.580
you've got a problem.

01:04:54.580 --> 01:04:56.450
But you've got a
problem there, and you

01:04:56.450 --> 01:04:58.200
have to deal with it there.

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:01.940
Because if you get mercury into
your oil distillation process,

01:05:01.940 --> 01:05:05.020
it really gums up the works
as far as I understand.

01:05:05.020 --> 01:05:06.717
So the companies
were saying, hey,

01:05:06.717 --> 01:05:08.550
this is not really an
international problem.

01:05:08.550 --> 01:05:10.480
This is something we deal with.

01:05:10.480 --> 01:05:12.770
We would really
prefer that you not

01:05:12.770 --> 01:05:16.290
regulate mercury and oil and
gas in an international way.

01:05:16.290 --> 01:05:19.770
And there were a lot of
countries on that bandwagon,

01:05:19.770 --> 01:05:21.550
too.

01:05:21.550 --> 01:05:26.732
Once it was clear that mercury
emissions regulations were not

01:05:26.732 --> 01:05:28.710
going to be applied
to oil and gas,

01:05:28.710 --> 01:05:33.240
Saudi Arabia decided that they
were going to go to lunch.

01:05:33.240 --> 01:05:36.830
So things like that.

01:05:36.830 --> 01:05:40.310
And again, awareness raising
of the kinds of things

01:05:40.310 --> 01:05:42.750
that international
industries do.

01:05:42.750 --> 01:05:47.050
So even if it's not
subject to the regulation,

01:05:47.050 --> 01:05:49.030
you have assessments
that come up

01:05:49.030 --> 01:05:51.570
that say, what are
best practices?

01:05:51.570 --> 01:05:54.760
Because your multinational
companies might know

01:05:54.760 --> 01:05:58.780
this is what you do when you
hit mercury in your gas deposit,

01:05:58.780 --> 01:06:02.910
but not all companies
might be aware of that.

01:06:02.910 --> 01:06:06.300
So again, that comes into the
capacity building, awareness

01:06:06.300 --> 01:06:09.070
raising, making
toolboxes to figure out

01:06:09.070 --> 01:06:11.910
how much mercury you're
emitting in your process.

01:06:11.910 --> 01:06:15.200
These things come out of
international negotiations

01:06:15.200 --> 01:06:18.539
a lot.

01:06:18.539 --> 01:06:21.410
AUDIENCE: The other
observation-- we

01:06:21.410 --> 01:06:25.750
we're going through
the importance of US

01:06:25.750 --> 01:06:31.946
and European relation to set
the way-- so in some sense,

01:06:31.946 --> 01:06:34.940
if you do what Europe
is doing, you're

01:06:34.940 --> 01:06:38.710
in pretty good shape in
terms of anticipating

01:06:38.710 --> 01:06:40.470
what could become global.

01:06:40.470 --> 01:06:41.686
Is that a fair assessment?

01:06:41.686 --> 01:06:43.102
NOELLE SELIN: I
think that's fair,

01:06:43.102 --> 01:06:44.930
and I think that's
a strategic choice.

01:06:44.930 --> 01:06:48.270
So one of the things that
that's changed over the years--

01:06:48.270 --> 01:06:50.150
it used to be that
the US was really

01:06:50.150 --> 01:06:53.800
the global standard leader in
international environmental

01:06:53.800 --> 01:06:54.340
things.

01:06:54.340 --> 01:06:56.300
And the US was kind
of a first mover

01:06:56.300 --> 01:06:58.530
in a lot of things
like the Clean Air Act,

01:06:58.530 --> 01:07:01.140
pesticide regulation, et cetera.

01:07:01.140 --> 01:07:03.960
And in the last decade,
decade and a half or so,

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:05.545
it's really been the EU.

01:07:05.545 --> 01:07:08.330
The EU is really the
global standard leader

01:07:08.330 --> 01:07:10.590
in the international
environment,

01:07:10.590 --> 01:07:12.210
particularly in
the chemicals area.

01:07:15.440 --> 01:07:18.480
And I think there's a
clear effort by the EU

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:23.380
to actually globalize
these kinds of standards.

01:07:23.380 --> 01:07:25.960
A strategic goal, in a sense.

01:07:25.960 --> 01:07:28.070
And part of that's
competitiveness, part of that

01:07:28.070 --> 01:07:32.680
is, well, we think it's
the right thing to do.

01:07:32.680 --> 01:07:34.970
Because it makes
everybody safer,

01:07:34.970 --> 01:07:38.200
and if we think something's too
dangerous for our population,

01:07:38.200 --> 01:07:42.740
why should it be OK for others?

01:07:42.740 --> 01:07:46.080
But again, with these kinds of
chemicals regulations that are

01:07:46.080 --> 01:07:50.150
going in the EU, you see that.

01:07:50.150 --> 01:07:53.120
Now, you do see
push back on that.

01:07:53.120 --> 01:07:56.560
The US saying, hey,
this is too far.

01:07:56.560 --> 01:08:00.630
And it ending up in trade
disputes and various things.

01:08:00.630 --> 01:08:02.400
You see that with CO2.

01:08:02.400 --> 01:08:08.250
But I think you do see
chemicals versions of that.

01:08:08.250 --> 01:08:12.090
But again, it's a
multi-level thing, too.

01:08:12.090 --> 01:08:15.140
In the US
traditionally how a lot

01:08:15.140 --> 01:08:17.189
of these environmental
regulations came to pass

01:08:17.189 --> 01:08:19.880
was that you have
a leading state.

01:08:19.880 --> 01:08:23.191
So the US regulation for the
Toxics Release Inventory,

01:08:23.191 --> 01:08:25.149
where you have to report
if you release toxics,

01:08:25.149 --> 01:08:29.100
came out of really a state
initiative in New Jersey first.

01:08:29.100 --> 01:08:32.359
So you get a few leader states.

01:08:32.359 --> 01:08:35.430
California does a lot
in terms of leading

01:08:35.430 --> 01:08:36.479
environmental regulation.

01:08:40.090 --> 01:08:42.979
The interaction between
California and the EU

01:08:42.979 --> 01:08:45.200
is actually really
interesting because you

01:08:45.200 --> 01:08:49.160
see California now copying
a lot of the EU regulations.

01:08:49.160 --> 01:08:51.740
You do see a lot
of copying as well.

01:08:51.740 --> 01:08:54.100
A lot of developing
countries when

01:08:54.100 --> 01:08:58.144
stressed with the idea of doing
environmental regulations says,

01:08:58.144 --> 01:09:01.020
gee, what's Germany doing?

01:09:01.020 --> 01:09:03.899
What's the US doing?

01:09:03.899 --> 01:09:06.580
Can we just go with that?

01:09:06.580 --> 01:09:08.880
Because again,
the capacity to do

01:09:08.880 --> 01:09:12.210
these kinds of real
technical analyses of, well,

01:09:12.210 --> 01:09:13.113
do we set it at five?

01:09:13.113 --> 01:09:14.029
Do we set it at seven?

01:09:14.029 --> 01:09:15.699
What does really make sense?

01:09:15.699 --> 01:09:17.790
A lot of developing
countries don't have that,

01:09:17.790 --> 01:09:21.320
so they say-- that's
really how China

01:09:21.320 --> 01:09:22.819
developed their
mercury threshold is

01:09:22.819 --> 01:09:24.656
took the one from Germany.

01:09:24.656 --> 01:09:27.670
I talked to the
Chinese researchers

01:09:27.670 --> 01:09:29.140
that have informed that.

01:09:29.140 --> 01:09:33.240
And there's a lot of
research on Mercury in China.

01:09:33.240 --> 01:09:35.700
But we've interviewed
them and they said, yeah,

01:09:35.700 --> 01:09:37.000
basically took Germany's.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.270
Seemed reasonable.

01:09:39.270 --> 01:09:40.760
And also that's
going to be where

01:09:40.760 --> 01:09:43.415
we're going to buy our emission
control equipment until we can

01:09:43.415 --> 01:09:45.790
figure out how to make it, so
if they're going to make it

01:09:45.790 --> 01:09:48.380
for German market,
we're not going

01:09:48.380 --> 01:09:49.880
to set a more
stringent one and then

01:09:49.880 --> 01:09:51.838
we're not going to be
able to buy the equipment

01:09:51.838 --> 01:09:54.270
and meet it until
we can make it.

01:09:54.270 --> 01:09:56.780
It just makes sense
with a globalized market

01:09:56.780 --> 01:09:57.606
for those things.

01:09:57.606 --> 01:10:00.750
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
that the Basel

01:10:00.750 --> 01:10:05.733
did the same for [INAUDIBLE],
copy just like that.

01:10:05.733 --> 01:10:08.720
They just didn't-- no local
analysis, no country--

01:10:08.720 --> 01:10:10.889
same thing.

01:10:10.889 --> 01:10:11.680
NOELLE SELIN: Yeah.

01:10:11.680 --> 01:10:14.030
But that's something
that you really start

01:10:14.030 --> 01:10:15.490
to see in these negotiations.

01:10:15.490 --> 01:10:19.370
So it's even more
prevalent in climate.

01:10:19.370 --> 01:10:20.820
But even in mercury
you see this,

01:10:20.820 --> 01:10:23.070
that a lot of
developing countries

01:10:23.070 --> 01:10:25.580
have one person at
this negotiation.

01:10:25.580 --> 01:10:29.370
US delegation was
about 20 people.

01:10:29.370 --> 01:10:32.030
so US would have
someone from the EPA,

01:10:32.030 --> 01:10:34.110
and someone from the
State Department,

01:10:34.110 --> 01:10:37.520
and someone from the
US Trade Rep's office,

01:10:37.520 --> 01:10:43.370
and they had some
health experts,

01:10:43.370 --> 01:10:46.806
they had people
that did vaccines.

01:10:49.530 --> 01:10:52.690
So they had a broad range
of expertise-- the emission

01:10:52.690 --> 01:10:54.515
control, the
products people, they

01:10:54.515 --> 01:10:58.000
were all in different groups.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:01.070
And even in mercury, which
is a fairly small area,

01:11:01.070 --> 01:11:03.060
you could assemble that team.

01:11:03.060 --> 01:11:05.850
Now, you've got people
from African countries

01:11:05.850 --> 01:11:07.240
and you've got one person.

01:11:07.240 --> 01:11:09.547
You've got two or three
groups going at the same time.

01:11:09.547 --> 01:11:11.630
You have to deal with
emissions from power plants.

01:11:11.630 --> 01:11:14.480
You have to deal with products.

01:11:14.480 --> 01:11:17.120
And the way it
works in the US is--

01:11:17.120 --> 01:11:19.460
I know the people who work
on mercury-- mercury's

01:11:19.460 --> 01:11:22.272
almost their whole job, because
they're dealing with mercury

01:11:22.272 --> 01:11:24.605
in Air Toxic Standards, they're
dealing with scientists,

01:11:24.605 --> 01:11:26.850
there are scientific
assessments going on.

01:11:26.850 --> 01:11:29.810
The person in a developing
country in mercury,

01:11:29.810 --> 01:11:33.110
they're probably running the
whole environment division.

01:11:33.110 --> 01:11:34.720
They might be
running environment

01:11:34.720 --> 01:11:37.800
and labor and health.

01:11:37.800 --> 01:11:40.550
Especially smaller
island states,

01:11:40.550 --> 01:11:44.700
you've got a couple of
hundred thousand people

01:11:44.700 --> 01:11:45.960
in your population.

01:11:45.960 --> 01:11:48.860
How much can you
environment ministry?

01:11:48.860 --> 01:11:50.660
So a lot of these
regional consultations

01:11:50.660 --> 01:11:52.040
become very important.

01:11:52.040 --> 01:11:55.330
But capacity really,
really comes into play.

01:11:55.330 --> 01:11:59.340
When we were at negotiations,
this negotiation to exhaustion

01:11:59.340 --> 01:12:00.510
comes in, too.

01:12:00.510 --> 01:12:02.720
Because like you
would expect, no one

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:05.010
wants to compromise till
the very last minute.

01:12:05.010 --> 01:12:07.700
So when we were there at the
final negotiating session,

01:12:07.700 --> 01:12:10.620
the deadline was-- the
meeting was scheduled

01:12:10.620 --> 01:12:13.980
through Friday, 6:00 PM.

01:12:13.980 --> 01:12:17.480
We got to agreement
Saturday morning at 8:00 AM

01:12:17.480 --> 01:12:19.560
after negotiating all night.

01:12:19.560 --> 01:12:23.440
So if you have a couple
people on your delegation,

01:12:23.440 --> 01:12:25.340
you can take naps.

01:12:25.340 --> 01:12:30.160
If you don't, you're
kind of challenged.

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:31.706
AUDIENCE: Take naps.

01:12:31.706 --> 01:12:32.590
NOELLE SELIN: Yeah.

01:12:32.590 --> 01:12:33.630
And you miss something.

01:12:33.630 --> 01:12:34.810
Yeah.

01:12:34.810 --> 01:12:36.920
Exactly.

01:12:36.920 --> 01:12:39.170
So again, you have to rely
on other friendly countries

01:12:39.170 --> 01:12:40.750
in the region.

01:12:40.750 --> 01:12:44.060
And a lot of that is done
to try to facilitate--

01:12:44.060 --> 01:12:46.640
in a sense, a lot of
the African countries

01:12:46.640 --> 01:12:51.430
have a lot in common in the
negotiation and sort of bond

01:12:51.430 --> 01:12:54.000
together.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:56.899
But again, countries that have
a very particular interest

01:12:56.899 --> 01:12:58.190
might not get that represented.

01:12:58.190 --> 01:13:00.200
And then they have to
go back and figure out

01:13:00.200 --> 01:13:03.100
what it means for
their own legislation

01:13:03.100 --> 01:13:06.055
in the context of all the other
things that they're doing.

01:13:06.055 --> 01:13:08.320
AUDIENCE: So will
you please talk again

01:13:08.320 --> 01:13:09.640
about this pace of negotiation?

01:13:09.640 --> 01:13:12.640
Because I remember I saw in one
of your talks about basically

01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:17.410
how exactly the dynamics
of the negotiation--

01:13:17.410 --> 01:13:19.220
so this kind of explains--

01:13:19.220 --> 01:13:20.900
NOELLE SELIN: So
yeah, nothing happens

01:13:20.900 --> 01:13:24.300
until the very last minute,
which is interesting.

01:13:24.300 --> 01:13:26.820
It's sort of like grad school.

01:13:26.820 --> 01:13:31.010
But there's a lot
of spinning wheels

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:35.440
for we have to discuss things,
we have to be deliberate.

01:13:35.440 --> 01:13:41.105
Again, 2002 was when there was
a global scientific assessment

01:13:41.105 --> 01:13:43.380
that says we ought to
do something about it.

01:13:43.380 --> 01:13:46.540
And then years and years.

01:13:46.540 --> 01:13:49.570
Mandate for
negotiations was 2009.

01:13:49.570 --> 01:13:52.380
So then you schedule a meeting.

01:13:52.380 --> 01:13:53.950
Usually scheduled
meetings may be

01:13:53.950 --> 01:13:57.310
for a negotiation like this
every six months or so,

01:13:57.310 --> 01:13:59.460
five or six day meeting.

01:13:59.460 --> 01:14:01.930
Everyone has to get there.

01:14:01.930 --> 01:14:03.910
You've got
interpretation issues.

01:14:03.910 --> 01:14:08.710
So the six UN languages
are simultaneously

01:14:08.710 --> 01:14:12.900
interpreted in the main room
in main plenary discussions.

01:14:12.900 --> 01:14:14.530
Most of the in the
card discussions

01:14:14.530 --> 01:14:18.240
are in English because
everyone speaks English

01:14:18.240 --> 01:14:20.180
except for a few.

01:14:20.180 --> 01:14:22.740
And if you're one of the few
that doesn't speak English,

01:14:22.740 --> 01:14:26.010
that's a problem.

01:14:26.010 --> 01:14:27.850
We try to avoid
sending those people.

01:14:27.850 --> 01:14:30.800
But some countries don't
have a great English speaking

01:14:30.800 --> 01:14:31.370
capacity.

01:14:31.370 --> 01:14:33.950
That's been mostly a
problem in my experience

01:14:33.950 --> 01:14:36.444
with French-speaking
African countries,

01:14:36.444 --> 01:14:39.200
have the most problem with
finding the person who speaks

01:14:39.200 --> 01:14:40.780
English.

01:14:40.780 --> 01:14:43.180
Lately it's been
a little better.

01:14:43.180 --> 01:14:47.120
The older people often
didn't speak English.

01:14:47.120 --> 01:14:49.950
Younger people are actually
sort of taken over now

01:14:49.950 --> 01:14:51.640
in a lot of these countries.

01:14:51.640 --> 01:14:58.980
And so the idea of the 65 year
old person that didn't quite

01:14:58.980 --> 01:15:03.740
get the message that
English was-- wasn't taught

01:15:03.740 --> 01:15:07.480
English in school is no longer
at the head of the delegation.

01:15:07.480 --> 01:15:10.139
It's now the 40 year
old that basically

01:15:10.139 --> 01:15:11.680
went to school in
an English speaking

01:15:11.680 --> 01:15:14.480
country in a lot
of these countries.

01:15:14.480 --> 01:15:16.778
So that's one issue.

01:15:16.778 --> 01:15:18.444
Again, if your country's
language is not

01:15:18.444 --> 01:15:19.660
one of the six UN
languages, you've

01:15:19.660 --> 01:15:21.451
got to speak on that
language on the floor.

01:15:21.451 --> 01:15:24.109
So if you're from
Brazil, you're probably

01:15:24.109 --> 01:15:26.400
speaking English on the floor
because Portuguese is not

01:15:26.400 --> 01:15:27.770
a UN language.

01:15:27.770 --> 01:15:30.290
So again, if you're
from Japan, you're

01:15:30.290 --> 01:15:33.110
probably speaking English on
the floor unless for some reason

01:15:33.110 --> 01:15:34.477
you know French.

01:15:34.477 --> 01:15:36.060
But you've got to
pick one of the six.

01:15:36.060 --> 01:15:39.920
So English, French, Spanish,
Arabic, Chinese, and Russian.

01:15:39.920 --> 01:15:41.800
So that's another
thing that makes

01:15:41.800 --> 01:15:43.480
things go fairly
slowly, when you have

01:15:43.480 --> 01:15:46.100
simultaneous interpretation.

01:15:46.100 --> 01:15:50.510
And it means that it can kind
of be a glacial pace for awhile

01:15:50.510 --> 01:15:53.880
while people say, hello,
I'm going to thank

01:15:53.880 --> 01:15:55.330
the chair for negotiations.

01:15:55.330 --> 01:15:56.960
And I want to
respectfully say that I

01:15:56.960 --> 01:16:00.530
disagree with paragraph two.

01:16:00.530 --> 01:16:02.680
But in a 10 minute speech.

01:16:02.680 --> 01:16:04.810
And then the next
person says I also

01:16:04.810 --> 01:16:06.030
disagree with paragraph two.

01:16:06.030 --> 01:16:09.300
And you have to go through
everybody in the countries

01:16:09.300 --> 01:16:11.780
before they actually
say, you all

01:16:11.780 --> 01:16:15.290
go talk about paragraph
two in the room over there.

01:16:15.290 --> 01:16:18.130
Once that happens and
you get to a deadline,

01:16:18.130 --> 01:16:20.950
you can agree on paragraph
two relatively rapidly.

01:16:20.950 --> 01:16:26.930
But you need that whole process
of getting to agreement there.

01:16:26.930 --> 01:16:29.300
So again, writing the
text-- the secretariat

01:16:29.300 --> 01:16:32.460
supports a lot of that.

01:16:32.460 --> 01:16:34.410
But again, you're
drafting in a big group

01:16:34.410 --> 01:16:37.910
of people with 160
countries going word

01:16:37.910 --> 01:16:42.260
by word through a document
that has legal force.

01:16:42.260 --> 01:16:44.301
It's a tough thing.

01:16:44.301 --> 01:16:46.800
And that's why the science, I
think, doesn't really come in.

01:16:46.800 --> 01:16:51.370
Because the complexity of
the negotiations, it's part

01:16:51.370 --> 01:16:54.720
of the reason why I think
the chemicals program has set

01:16:54.720 --> 01:16:57.287
up this process pretty
well, is that they say,

01:16:57.287 --> 01:16:59.120
we're going to do the
scientific assessment.

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:00.451
We're all going to agree.

01:17:00.451 --> 01:17:01.450
We're going to stamp it.

01:17:01.450 --> 01:17:03.117
We're going to move on.

01:17:03.117 --> 01:17:04.700
If you have a question
on the science,

01:17:04.700 --> 01:17:06.491
we'll kick it back to
the scientific group,

01:17:06.491 --> 01:17:09.160
we'll do an assessment,
we'll agree, we'll move on.

01:17:09.160 --> 01:17:11.700
So it's kind of like the
science sets the basis

01:17:11.700 --> 01:17:13.720
and then we're
going to negotiate,

01:17:13.720 --> 01:17:17.740
which means it's not
always the optimal outcome.

01:17:17.740 --> 01:17:21.210
But it gets done.

01:17:21.210 --> 01:17:22.230
Something gets done.

01:17:22.230 --> 01:17:24.950
Now I did some analysis
actually of what

01:17:24.950 --> 01:17:26.700
would happen in mercury
in the environment

01:17:26.700 --> 01:17:30.920
as a result of this treaty
with the best guesses of what

01:17:30.920 --> 01:17:32.290
it would involve.

01:17:32.290 --> 01:17:37.480
And pretty much the conclusion
was avoided increases.

01:17:37.480 --> 01:17:40.790
So without the treaty,
our business as usual

01:17:40.790 --> 01:17:43.090
would be mercury increasing
in the environment.

01:17:43.090 --> 01:17:45.699
With the treaty,
probably pretty steady.

01:17:45.699 --> 01:17:48.240
So again, if you want mercury
to decrease in the environment,

01:17:48.240 --> 01:17:51.750
you've got to then go through
and look at your technology

01:17:51.750 --> 01:17:53.730
regulations for
emissions and probably

01:17:53.730 --> 01:17:59.110
ratchet those down through
the treaty process itself.

01:17:59.110 --> 01:18:02.690
Otherwise, you're not
going to actually improve.

01:18:02.690 --> 01:18:05.020
It's also more legally
and politically

01:18:05.020 --> 01:18:07.600
important at this point then
environmentally important

01:18:07.600 --> 01:18:10.660
because it sends a pretty
clear message that mercury

01:18:10.660 --> 01:18:13.290
is a pretty bad thing
internationally,

01:18:13.290 --> 01:18:17.940
and that has a really
big signaling mechanism.

01:18:17.940 --> 01:18:22.460
If you're a company and you're
thinking about using mercury

01:18:22.460 --> 01:18:25.590
in a process-- which might be
the easiest way to do things,

01:18:25.590 --> 01:18:29.470
because mercury has some really
neat chemical properties--

01:18:29.470 --> 01:18:32.980
this kind of thing will make
you think twice about it.

01:18:32.980 --> 01:18:39.230
So that idea that there's sort
of a consensus around mercury

01:18:39.230 --> 01:18:42.300
is bad, and they're increasing
amounts of regulation,

01:18:42.300 --> 01:18:47.790
and countries are beginning to
figure out that mercury is now

01:18:47.790 --> 01:18:54.230
going to regulate more has
a strong political force,

01:18:54.230 --> 01:18:56.280
whereas the technical
regulations might not

01:18:56.280 --> 01:18:58.642
be the operative part.

01:18:58.642 --> 01:19:00.475
So again, legally and
politically important.

01:19:00.475 --> 01:19:02.810
Not so much
environmentally yet-- but

01:19:02.810 --> 01:19:05.640
might be in the future
as amendments come in,

01:19:05.640 --> 01:19:08.030
as the technical
requirements-- there's

01:19:08.030 --> 01:19:11.200
a lot to be decided on
exactly what technologies

01:19:11.200 --> 01:19:13.555
might be considered in terms
of emissions regulations.

01:19:13.555 --> 01:19:16.520
And that's an open
question right now.

01:19:16.520 --> 01:19:19.760
And it's going to be decided
by the technical groups

01:19:19.760 --> 01:19:24.420
and by conference of
parties negotiations.

01:19:24.420 --> 01:19:25.326
Yes?

01:19:25.326 --> 01:19:27.664
AUDIENCE: So after ten
years of working on this,

01:19:27.664 --> 01:19:30.020
do you eat fish?

01:19:30.020 --> 01:19:32.650
NOELLE SELIN: I do eat fish.

01:19:32.650 --> 01:19:35.460
There are fish that are
relatively low in mercury.

01:19:35.460 --> 01:19:41.150
So the key in dietary
advice on mercury

01:19:41.150 --> 01:19:44.420
is you don't want
people not eating fish.

01:19:44.420 --> 01:19:48.650
Fish high in omega 3s, but low
in mercury-- unfortunately,

01:19:48.650 --> 01:19:50.230
that's the herrings
of the world.

01:19:50.230 --> 01:19:51.960
And I don't want herring.

01:19:51.960 --> 01:19:55.017
But again, I also
figure there's lots

01:19:55.017 --> 01:19:57.600
of things that are going to kill
me faster, like French fries.

01:19:57.600 --> 01:20:02.980
So you've got to take
them one at a time.

01:20:02.980 --> 01:20:06.964
PROFESSOR: Any more questions?

01:20:06.964 --> 01:20:08.458
Thank you very much.

